# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: almond
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] The flowering staff of Aaron in the biblical narrative may be an etiology of the asherah cultic object.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] Aaron’s rod, originally associated with priestly and magical powers, may have been later transferred to Moses in various biblical accounts, demonstrating his authority and divine empowerment.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] In Israelite culture, the rod (Hebrew: מַטֶּה *maṭṭeh*) was a natural symbol of authority, as the tool used by the shepherd to correct and guide his flock.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] Moses, in fact, initially carried his rod while tending his sheep, and later it became his symbol of authority over the Israelites.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] The rods of both Moses and Aaron were endowed with miraculous power during the Plagues of Egypt.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] God commanded Moses to raise his rod over the Red Sea when it was to be split and in prayer over Israel in battle; at Meribah Moses brought forth water from a stone using his rod.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] Aaron's rod – perhaps a different rod – reappears in Numbers 16–17.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] Here Korah's rebellion against Moses's proclamation of the tribe of Levi as the priesthood has been quashed and the entire congregation's ensuing rebellion has resulted in a plague, ended only by the intercession of Moses and Aaron.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] In order to "stop the complaints" of the Israelites, God commands that each of the Twelve Tribes provide a rod; and only that of the tribe chosen to become priests will miraculously sprout overnight.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] Aaron provides his rod to represent the tribe of Levi, and "it put forth buds, produced blossoms, and bore ripe almonds", as an evidence of the exclusive right to the priesthood of the tribe of Levi.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] In commemoration of this decision, it was commanded that the rod be stored "before the testimony".
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] Aaron's rod is cited as exhibiting miraculous power on its own, when not physically held by its owner.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] In Exodus 7:10–1, Aaron "cast down his rod" and it became a serpent.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] When he does so, the Pharaoh's sorcerers counter by similarly casting down their own rods, which also become serpents, but Aaron's rod swallowed them all.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] Similarly, in Numbers 17:23 it sprouted blossoms when not being held.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] Rabbinic midrash described attributes of Aaron's rod beyond those in the Biblical text.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] It is reported that the rod was made of sapphire, weighed forty seahs (a seah = 10.70 pounds), and bore the inscription דצ״ך עד״ש באח״ב (the initials of the Hebrew names of the Ten Plagues).
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] God created it in the twilight of the sixth day of Creation, and delivered it to Adam when the latter was driven from paradise.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] After it had passed through the hands of Shem, Enoch, Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob successively, it came into the possession of Joseph.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] On Joseph's death the Egyptian nobles stole some of his belongings, and, among them, Jethro appropriated the staff.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] Jethro planted the staff in his garden, when its marvelous virtue was revealed by the fact that nobody could withdraw it from the ground (compare "the sword in the stone"); even to touch it was fraught with danger to life.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] This was because the Ineffable Name of God was engraved upon it.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] When Moses entered Jethro's household he read the Name, and by means of it was able to draw up the rod, for which service Zipporah, Jethro's daughter, was given to him in marriage.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] Her father had sworn that she should become the wife of the man who should be able to master the miraculous rod and of no other.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] Aaron's rod, together with its blossoms and fruit, was preserved in the Ark.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] King Josiah, who foresaw the impending national catastrophe, concealed the Ark and the objects stored with it (Aaron's rod, a vial of manna, and the holy anointing oil).
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] Their whereabouts will remain unknown until, in the Messianic age, the prophet Elijah shall reveal them.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] The length of the rod can be determined by the size of the ark of the covenant as stated in Exodus 37:1 or a length of 2.5 cubits, a depth of 1.5 cubits, and a height of 1.5 cubits.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] The cubit was not defined in either SI or Imperial units.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] However, the average of the two lengths given by Rav Avraham Chaim Naeh or Chazon Ish would put a cubit at roughly 1.7 feet, putting the maximum length of the staff at 6.1' (6'1.2" or 1.9m).
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] (Correction to the immediately above paragraph: The two hypotenuses referenced are not at right angles to each other, hence the Pythagorean formula does not apply to the third side.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] As discussed, the Bible ascribes similar miraculous powers to rods of Aaron and Moses.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] According to one midrash, Moses split a tree trunk into twelve portions, and gave one portion to each tribe.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] When the Rod of Aaron produced blossoms, the Israelites could not but acknowledge the significance of the token.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] This opinion seemingly assumes that the rod in Korach's rebellion was separate from the rod used for the plagues.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] Hebrews 9:4 states that Aaron's rod was kept in the Ark of the Covenant.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] The account of the blossoming of Aaron's rod contained in Clement's first letter to the Corinthians (ep.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] 43) is in haggadic-midrashic style, and may probably be ascribed to Jewish or, more strictly speaking, Jewish-Hellenistic sources.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] According to that account, Moses placed upon each of the twelve staffs the corresponding seal of the head of a tribe.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] The doors of the sanctuary were similarly sealed, to prevent anyone from having access to the rods at night.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] The miraculous flowering of the rod was also considered a type of the Incarnation of Christ and his Virgin Birth, and appears in scenes of the Annunciation to Mary.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] Accounts of Aaron's rod appear in Islamic literature.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] 1035, AH 427) Stories of the Prophets depicts Harun (Aaron) leaning on his rod, while his brother Musa's (Moses) staff miraculously turned into a snake-dragon to defeat Pharaoh's magicians.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] Lawrence entitled a novel *Aaron's Rod* in 1922.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] This book describes a flautist, Aaron Sissons, and his experiences as he journeys through a Europe exhausted by the First World War.
[src:almond/aaron-s-rod] The biblical eponymous reference, with the flute representing a magic rod, is intended to be ironic.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] As the primary news division of the ABC, it is responsible for all news-gathering and coverage across the public broadcaster's various television, radio, and online platforms.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] ABC News has an extensive online presence which includes written news reports and videos, an ABC News mobile app (ABC Listen), podcasts, and in addition, all of the ABC News television programs available via the video-on-demand platform, ABC iview.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] As of 2021, the ABC News website includes ABC Sport, ABC Health, ABC Science, ABC Arts & Culture, ABC Fact Check, ABC Environment, and news in other languages.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] Simon Robinson was appointed director of the division on 28 May 2026.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] ABC News, from its inception in 1932, with ABC radio sourced its news from multiple sources, including cable news from London, its own bureaus in Europe, the Middle East and the Asia-Pacific, and in a fashion similar to commercial radio stations from local newspapers around Australia.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] Censorship was rife during the war, particularly after the U.S. entered the conflict on 7 December 1941.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] After General Douglas MacArthur set up his headquarters in Australia, he wielded enormous power, including on matters of censorship.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] Inter alia, he declared that every Australian radio station would only broadcast three news bulletins per day and that these would be simultaneous on all stations (ABC and commercial) at 7.45 a.m., midday, and 7.00 p.m.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] Weather forecasts were banned because it was felt that these may assist the enemy.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] The 7:45 a.m. bulletin was the only one that did not commence on the hour or the half-hour.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] It was placed at this timeslot as initially the ABC sourced its news from newspapers in a deal which required that news would not be broadcast earlier, to ensure newspapers sales were not affected.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] This bulletin continued at this time on ABC Local Radio stations until 19 September 2020, before being cancelled to save costs.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] Notices were issued banning radio stations from broadcasting some major wartime events, but as the federal government did not have the same power over the printed press as it did over the radio, newspapers usually reported events that radio was not permitted to mention.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] The ABC launched its first independent news bulletin on 1 June 1947 after years of negotiations with the Australian Government.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] The *Australian Broadcasting Corporation Act 1983* mandates that the ABC "shall develop and maintain an independent service for the broadcasting of news and information" both within Australia on a daily basis, and also to countries outside Australia.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] The name of the division and director responsible has changed over the years.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] In 2004 it was the News and Current Affairs Division when John Cameron took over as Director from Max Uechtritz as Director.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] The financial year 2008–2009 saw a lot of changes, both in the way that television content was produced as well as an "expansion of international news programming and continuous news across platforms, new programs and a range of appointments to senior positions".
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] Kate Torney became director of the News Division in April 2009.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] In November 2014, a cut of A$254 million to funding over the following five years meant that the ABC would have to shed about 10% of its total staff, around 400 people.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] There were several programming changes, with regional and local programming losing out to national programs, and the Adelaide TV production studio had to close apart from the news and current affairs section.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] In late 2015 Gaven Morris was appointed Director of the News Division.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] On 10 April 2017, ABC News introduced a new visual identity; as part of the changes, ABC News 24 and ABC NewsRadio were both rebranded as simply "ABC News", while their previously-separate social media presences were merged and unified under ABC News accounts.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] The Director's role changed its name to Director, News, Analysis & Investigations in 2017–2018, and as of June 2021 Morris was still in the role.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] During the 2017 to 2018 financial year, the ABC launched "Regional Connecting Communities" program, which provided funding for increased jobs in the regions, as well as more resources for local news, weather and live reporting.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] Justin Stevens was appointed director of the division of ABC News, Analysis and Investigations on 31 March 2022.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] Media executive and producer Kimberly Lynton "Kim" Williams AM was appointed chair of ABC News on 7 March 2024, with the term expected to conclude on 6 March 2029.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] In March 2026, staff at ABC began a one-day strike over pay and working conditions.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] This was the first walk out in 20 years.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] The division is responsible for all news-gathering and production of news output for ABC television, the ABC network of radio stations, and for its online services.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] In 2018 it was estimated that online ABC news and current affairs reached about 4.8 million users in Australia each month.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] As of 2021, the ABC News website includes ABC Sport, ABC Health, ABC Science, ABC Arts & Culture, ABC Fact Check, ABC Environment and news in other languages.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] The news theme used from the first days of ABC television from November 1956 to 1985 was "Majestic Fanfare", composed by Charles Williams.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] From 1956 until the early 1980s the version used was the abridged version performed by the Queen's Hall Light Orchestra, from a recording made in 1943.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] Each bulletin opened with a clip from the top story of the day, with the title "ABC News" superimposed over the footage.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] Later, this on-screen approach was replaced by a generic graphic title sequence.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] In 1982, to celebrate the ABC's 50th anniversary, a new version of the theme was commissioned, which incorporated both orchestral and new electronic elements.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] With the exception of a period in the mid-1980s, during which a synthesised theme ("Best Endeavours", written by Alan Hawkshaw, which was the theme for Channel 4 News in the UK) was used for around a year, this was used on radio until August 1988, and on television until early 1985.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] A reworking of "Majestic Fanfare" (essentially the original orchestration up one tone) was arranged by Richard Mills and recorded in 1988 by the Sydney Symphony Orchestra.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] From 1985, a theme composed by Tony Ansell and Peter Wall was used for 20 years, even after the 1998 brand refresh.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] In 2010, it was sampled and remixed by the group Pendulum and this revised work went on to be placed #11 on the Triple J Hottest 100 chart on Australia Day 2011.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] The theme for ABC News changed on Australia Day (26 January) 2005, to a piece written by Martin Armiger and John Gray, and for a couple of years it bore a resemblance to the original Peter Wall / Tony Ansell work in the opening signature notes.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] Wall challenged the ABC and was successful in reaching an agreement.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] The opening notes were removed and the work was re-arranged in 2010.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] The theme music from the 2005–2010 era was remixed by Armiger, giving it a more upbeat, synthesised feel.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] In August 2024, the Ansell–Wall theme was revived in an updated form as part of a larger rebranding of ABC News.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] The theme was remastered by David McDonald from the original multi-track studio recording, including a rerecorded piccolo, and layered samples of a children's drumkit (which McDonald had originally bought for his daughter) to add a bassier sound.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] On 4 March 1985, the ABC refreshed its structure and look, when the 7 o'clock news and the following current affairs program (at that time, *Nationwide*) were combined to form *The National*, and moved to 6:30 pm until 8 December 1985.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] After *The National* was deemed unsuccessful, On 9 December 1985, the news was refreshed again with a new set, graphics, and theme.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] In 1998, the set was updated, a new opener featuring a light blue globe and the ABC logo was introduced, and the theme remained the same but was tweaked.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] The graphics also changed to match the new look.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] On Australia Day (26 January) 2005, a new look (along with theme music) was introduced.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] The new look made use of an orange and blue globe motif.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] At the same time the set and graphics received a major overhaul to fit in with this look.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] This package was used until 21 July 2010, a day before the launch of ABC News.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] In January 2010, the ABC announced that a dedicated 24-hour digital television news channel, named ABC News 24 would be launched during the year.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] The new channel commenced preliminary broadcasting with a promo loop in early July 2010, with the ABC re-numbering ABC HD channel 20 to logical channel number 24.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] The channel was officially launched as ABC News 24 at 7:30 pm Australian Eastern Standard Time on 22 July 2010, and simulcast its first hour of transmission on ABC1.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] With the launch of ABC News on 22 July 2010, all 7 pm bulletins across Australia had a graphics overhaul to match the look of the new channel.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] The blue/orange globe style opener was replaced with a series of sliding panels, featuring images specific to each state.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] New sets were built in each capital city studio to match the ABC News 24 set and graphics were changed to match.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] The news bulletins such as *News Breakfast*, *ABC News Mornings*, *ABC News at Noon, ABC News Day,* *ABC News Afternoons*, *The World*, *ABC Late News* and *Weekend Breakfast* are aired on ABC News along with its own 30- and 15-minute hourly bulletins.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] National news updates are presented on ABC TV throughout the day, with evening updates at 7 pm presented live in most states by the respective state news presenters.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] Bulletins focus strongly on issues of state relevance, with a greater inclusion of national and international news items than are found in the news bulletins of commercial broadcasters.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] A national financial bulletin is presented on weeknights by Alan Kohler in Melbourne.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] The ABC's Ultimo studios produces the 8:30 pm weeknight update presented by Joe O'Brien.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] News and current affairs programs are also broadcast on ABC Australia, a channel broadcast to the region outside Australia.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] These include *Four Corners*, *7:30* and *Q+A*.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] ABC news television programs are available via the video-on-demand platform, ABC iview.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] ABC NewsRadio is a radio station dedicated to news and current affairs.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] It features national news bulletins at :00 and :30, with rolling news coverage during the remainder of each hour.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] In off-peak hours, it broadcasts content from partner providers such as the BBC World Service, NPR, and Deutsche Welle.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] Radio Australia, which covers the Asia-Pacific region, broadcasts regular bulletins produced in Melbourne, featuring reports from foreign correspondents in the region.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] State bulletins are produced by the ABC Local Radio station from the capital city of each state and mainland territory.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] They are broadcast to all ABC Local Radio and Radio National stations in each state, and focus strongly on issues of state relevance, but also feature national and international stories.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] National bulletins air when state bulletins are not produced.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] ABC Local Radio stations previously broadcast a flagship 15-minute state bulletin at 7:45 am, which in its final years was the only bulletin still introduced by the 18-second version of Majestic Fanfare.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] All other bulletins were introduced by a 9-second version of Majestic Fanfare.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] This bulletin began in 1939 and was discontinued on Sunday 20 September 2020.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] ABC News produces several current affairs programs for radio.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] All share a quasi-magazine format, and investigate stories in greater depth compared to news bulletins.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] All ABC radio stations are available via an ABC News mobile app, ABC Listen, from which podcasts are also available.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] In March 2024, ABC News won the 2023 Gold Lizzie for Best Title at the IT Journalism Awards, a shared honour between ABC News Story Lab and ABC Radio.
[src:almond/abc-news-australia] ABC News also won Best Gaming Coverage and Best News Coverage.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] A plant will abscise a part either to discard a member that is no longer necessary, such as a leaf during autumn, or a flower following fertilisation, or for the purposes of reproduction.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] Most deciduous plants drop their leaves by abscission before winter, whereas evergreen plants continuously abscise their leaves.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] Another form of abscission is fruit drop, when a plant abscises fruit while still immature in order to conserve resources needed to bring the remaining fruit to maturity.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] If a leaf is damaged, a plant may also abscise it to conserve water or photosynthetic efficiency, depending on the 'costs' to the plant as a whole.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] The abscission layer is a greenish-greyish color.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] Abscission can also occur in premature leaves as a means of plant defense.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] Premature leaf abscission has been shown to occur in response to infestation by gall aphids.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] By abscising leaves that have been made host to aphid galls, plants have been shown to massively diminish the pest population, as 98% of aphids in abscised galls died.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] The abscission is selective, and the chance of dropping leaves increases as the number of galls increases.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] A leaf with three or more galls was four times more likely to abscise than a leaf with one, and 20 times as likely to be dropped as a leaf without any galls.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] Abscission occurs in a sequence of three steps: resorption, protective layer formation, and detachment.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] The latter two steps may occur in either order, depending on species.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] Resorption involves degrading chlorophyll to extract the majority of its nutrients.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] Nitrogen is found in chlorophyll and is often a limiting nutrient for plants, which need large quantities to form amino acids, nucleic acids, proteins, and certain plant hormones.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] Once nitrogen and other nutrients have been extracted from chlorophyll, the nutrients will travel to other tissues of the plant.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] Resorption is what causes leaves in the fall to change colors.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] Carotenoids in the leaves are slower to degrade than chlorophyll, so autumn leaves appear yellow and orange.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] Cells under the abscission zone divide and form a layer of cork cells.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] Situated on both sides of the abscission zone are layers of parenchyma cells, which produce and inject suberin and lignin under the abscission zone into the new layer of cork cells.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] Suberin and lignin create a durable and waterproof layer for the plant once the organ is detached.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] This step can occur in a variety of ways depending on the species but always occurs at the abscission zone.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] Detachment can occur when layers of parenchyma cells secrete cell wall enzymes to self-digest the middle lamella, which holds the cell walls together at the abscission zone.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] This causes the cells of the abscission zone to break apart and the leaf or other plant part to fall off.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] Another way detachment occurs is through imbibition of water.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] The plant cells at the abscission zone will take in a large amount of water, swell, and eventually burst, making the organ fall off.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] Once detached, the protective layer of cork will be exposed.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] In deciduous trees, an abscission zone, also called a separation zone, is formed at the base of the petiole.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] It is composed of a top layer that has cells with weak walls, and a bottom layer that expands in the autumn, breaking the weak walls of the cells in the top layer.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] The reduction of chlorophyll production in leaves due to decreased sunlight in the autumn explains why some leaves turn yellow.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] However, the yellow color can attract aphids, so some trees turn the leaves red instead by injecting a bright pigment.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] The loss of chlorophyll may also contribute to the abscission process.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] A variety of reactive oxygen species (ROS) are generated by plants during times of stress (biotic and abiotic), including UV light, cool temperatures, excessive light, pathogens, parasites, and high salinity.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] The presence and continuous production of these ROS causes disruption in the homeostasis of the cellular components, leading to metabolic dysfunction and expression of cell wall-degrading enzymes (WDEs).
[src:almond/abscission-layer] While researchers originally believed abscisic acid to be the hormone that stimulates abscission (for which the hormone was named), it was later proved that it does not play a primary role.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] In fact, auxin, a plant hormone, and ethylene have been implicated as prominent regulators of abscission signaling.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] The two compounds work in a synergistic fashion: As the auxin levels decrease, the flux of auxin to the abscission zone is reduced.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] Exhaustion of auxin makes the abscission zone sensitive to ethylene.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] When the plant is then exposed to ethylene, gene expression of cell wall-degrading enzymes such as cellulase and polygalacturonase are activated.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] However, this is not to say that ethylene directly activates WDE gene expression, because the elements responsible for detecting ethylene have not been found in the gene's promoter region.
[src:almond/abscission-layer] Dwindling auxin levels have also been implicated in autumn-leaf color change.
[src:almond/acorn] The **acorn** is the nut of the oaks and their close relatives (genera *Quercus*, *Notholithocarpus* and *Lithocarpus*, in the family Fagaceae); alternatively known as **glans**.
[src:almond/acorn] It usually contains a seedling surrounded by two cotyledons (seedling leaves), enclosed in a tough shell known as the pericarp, and borne in a cup-shaped cupule.
[src:almond/acorn] Acorns take between 5 and 24 months (depending on the species) to mature; see the list of *Quercus* species for details of oak classification, in which acorn morphology and phenology are important factors.
[src:almond/acorn] The word *acorn* (earlier *akerne*, and *acharn*) is related to the Gothic name *akran*, which had the sense of "fruit of the unenclosed land".
[src:almond/acorn] The word was applied to the most important forest produce, that of the oak.
[src:almond/acorn] Chaucer spoke of "achornes of okes" in the 14th century.
[src:almond/acorn] By degrees, popular etymology connected the word both with "corn" and "oak-horn", and the spelling changed accordingly.
[src:almond/acorn] 15th–16th century) derives from association with *ac* (Old English: "oak") + *corn*.
[src:almond/acorn] The Latin *glans* as found in many literature regarding it originally applies to any nut is the root of several Romance words for the acorn (the French *gland*, Catalan *gla*, Italian *ghianda*) cognate to Greek βάλανος, which also extends to the vascular penile tip from similarity in shape.
[src:almond/acorn] Acorns play an important role in forest ecology when oaks are plentiful or dominant in the landscape.
[src:almond/acorn] The volume of the acorn crop may vary widely, creating great abundance or great stress on the many animals dependent on acorns and the predators of those animals.
[src:almond/acorn] Acorns, along with other nuts, are termed mast.
[src:almond/acorn] Wildlife that consume acorns as an important part of their diets include birds, such as jays, pigeons, some ducks, and several species of woodpeckers.
[src:almond/acorn] Small mammals that feed on acorns include mice, squirrels and several other rodents.
[src:almond/acorn] One beetle species, *Thorectes lusitanicus*, also feeds on acorns.
[src:almond/acorn] Acorns have a large influence on small rodents in their habitats, as large acorn yields help rodent populations to grow.
[src:almond/acorn] Large mammals such as pigs, bears, and deer also consume large amounts of acorns; they may constitute up to 25% of the diet of deer in the autumn.
[src:almond/acorn] In Spain, Portugal and the New Forest region of southern England, pigs are still turned loose in *dehesas* (large oak groves) in the autumn, to fill and fatten themselves on acorns.
[src:almond/acorn] Heavy consumption of acorns can, on the other hand, be toxic to other animals that cannot detoxify their tannins, such as horses and cattle, especially if eaten in excess.
[src:almond/acorn] The larvae of some moths and weevils also live in young acorns, consuming the kernels as they develop.
[src:almond/acorn] Acorns are attractive to animals because they are large and thus efficiently consumed or cached.
[src:almond/acorn] Percentages vary from species to species, but all acorns contain large amounts of protein, carbohydrates and fats, as well as the minerals calcium, phosphorus and potassium, and the vitamin niacin.
[src:almond/acorn] Total food energy in an acorn also varies by species, but all compare well with other wild foods and with other nuts.
[src:almond/acorn] Acorns also contain bitter tannins, the amount varying with the species.
[src:almond/acorn] Since tannins, which are plant polyphenols, interfere with an animal's ability to metabolize protein, creatures must adapt in different ways to use the nutritional value acorns contain.
[src:almond/acorn] Animals may preferentially select acorns that contain fewer tannins.
[src:almond/acorn] When the tannins are metabolized in cattle, the tannic acid produced can cause ulceration and kidney failure.
[src:almond/acorn] Animals that cache acorns, such as jays and squirrels, may wait to consume some of these acorns until sufficient groundwater has percolated through them to leach out the tannins.
[src:almond/acorn] Other animals buffer their acorn diet with other foods.
[src:almond/acorn] Many insects, birds, and mammals metabolize tannins with fewer ill effects than do humans.
[src:almond/acorn] Species of acorn that contain large amounts of tannins are very bitter, astringent, and potentially irritating if eaten raw.
[src:almond/acorn] This is particularly true of the acorns of American red oaks and English oaks.
[src:almond/acorn] The acorns of white oaks, being much lower in tannins, are nutty in flavor; this characteristic is enhanced if the acorns are given a light roast before grinding.
[src:almond/acorn] Tannins can be removed by soaking chopped acorns in several changes of water, until the water no longer turns brown.
[src:almond/acorn] Cold water leaching can take several days, but three to four changes of boiling water can leach the tannins in under an hour.
[src:almond/acorn] Hot water leaching (boiling) cooks the starch of the acorn, which would otherwise act like gluten in flour, helping it bind to itself.
[src:almond/acorn] For this reason, if the acorns will be used to make flour, then cold water leaching is preferred.
[src:almond/acorn] Being rich in fat, acorn flour can spoil or molder easily and must be carefully stored.
[src:almond/acorn] Acorns are also sometimes prepared as a massage oil.
[src:almond/acorn] Acorns of the white oak group, *Leucobalanus*, typically start rooting as soon as they are in contact with the soil (in the fall), then send up the leaf shoot in the spring.
[src:almond/acorn] Acorns are too heavy for wind dispersal, so they require other ways to spread.
[src:almond/acorn] Oaks therefore depend on biological seed dispersal agents to move the acorns beyond the mother tree and into a suitable area for germination (including access to adequate water, sunlight and soil nutrients), ideally a minimum of 20–30 m (70–100 ft) from the parent tree.
[src:almond/acorn] Many animals eat unripe acorns on the tree or ripe acorns from the ground, with no reproductive benefit to the oak, but some animals, such as squirrels and jays serve as seed dispersal agents.
[src:almond/acorn] Jays and squirrels that scatter-hoard acorns in caches for future use effectively plant acorns in a variety of locations in which it is possible for them to germinate and thrive.
[src:almond/acorn] Even though jays and squirrels retain remarkably large mental maps of cache locations and return to eat them, the odd acorn may be lost, or a jay or squirrel may die before consuming all of its stores.
[src:almond/acorn] A small number of acorns manage to germinate and survive, producing the next generation of oaks.
[src:almond/acorn] Scatter-hoarding behavior depends on jays and squirrels associating with plants that provide good packets of food that are nutritionally valuable, but not too big for the dispersal agent to handle.
[src:almond/acorn] The beak sizes of jays determine how large acorns may get before jays ignore them.
[src:almond/acorn] Acorns germinate on different schedules, depending on their place in the oak family.
[src:almond/acorn] Once acorns sprout, they are less nutritious, as the seed tissue converts to the indigestible lignins that form the root.
[src:almond/acorn] In some cultures, acorns once constituted a dietary staple, though they have largely been replaced by grains and are now typically considered a relatively unimportant food, except in some Native American and Korean communities.
[src:almond/acorn] Several cultures have devised traditional acorn-leaching methods, sometimes involving specialized tools, that were traditionally passed on to their children by word of mouth.
[src:almond/acorn] Raw acorns are 28% water, 41% carbohydrates, 24% fat, and 6% protein (table).
[src:almond/acorn] In a reference amount of 100 g (3.5 oz), raw acorns supply 387 calories and are a rich source (20% or more of the Daily Value, DV) of vitamin B6, folate, copper, and manganese (table).
[src:almond/acorn] Acorns served an important role in early human history and were a source of food for many cultures around the world.
[src:almond/acorn] Dental microwear suggests that Neanderthals in Belgium consumed acorns among other hard foods.
[src:almond/acorn] Many modern human cultures relied on acorns, such as the Ancient Greek lower classes and the Japanese (during the Jōmon period), for instance.
[src:almond/acorn] In antiquity, Pliny the Elder noted that acorn flour could be used to make bread.
[src:almond/acorn] Acorns rarely form a large part of modern diets and are not currently cultivated on scales approaching that of many other nuts.
[src:almond/acorn] However, if properly prepared (by selecting high-quality specimens and leaching out the bitter tannins in water), acorn meal can be used in some recipes calling for grain flours.
[src:almond/acorn] Varieties of oak differ in the amount of tannin in their acorns.
[src:almond/acorn] Varieties preferred by Native Americans, such as *Quercus kelloggii* (California black oak), may be easier to prepare or more palatable.
[src:almond/acorn] Roasted acorn flour is a main ingredient in sweet cakes special to Kurdish areas of Iran and Iraq.
[src:almond/acorn] Acorns are a traditional food of many indigenous peoples of North America, and long served an especially important role for Californian Native Americans, where the ranges of several species of oaks overlap, increasing the reliability of the resource.
[src:almond/acorn] In the San Francisco Bay Area acorns found were often associated with grinding tools.
[src:almond/acorn] Stone tools like hammerstone and anvil, millingstones, and mortar and pestle help crack open the acorn and grind the acorn into dust.
[src:almond/acorn] Acorns and balanophagy (acorn-eating [fr]) were associated with ideas of primitive life and Arcadia in classical literature and beyond.
[src:almond/acorn] A motif in Roman architecture, also popular in Celtic and Scandinavian art, the acorn symbol is used as an ornament on cutlery, furniture, and jewelry; it also appears on finials at Westminster Abbey.
[src:almond/acorn] The acorn was used frequently by both Union and Confederate forces during the American Civil War.
[src:almond/acorn] Modern US Army Cavalry Scout campaign hats still retain traces of the acorn today.
[src:almond/acorn] The acorn is the symbol for the National Trails of England and Wales, and is used for the waymarks on these paths.
[src:almond/acorn] The acorn, specifically that of the white oak, is also present in the symbol for the University of Connecticut.
[src:almond/acorn] Acorns are also used as charges in heraldry.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Human habitation in Afghanistan dates to the Middle Paleolithic era.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Popularly referred to as the graveyard of empires, the land has witnessed numerous military campaigns, including those by the Persians, Alexander the Great, the Maurya Empire, Arab Muslims, the Mongols, the British, the Soviet Union, and a US-led coalition.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan also served as the source from which the Greco-Bactrians and the Mughals, among others, rose to form major empires.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Because of the various conquests and periods in both the Iranian and Indian cultural spheres, the area was a center for Zoroastrianism, Buddhism, Hinduism, and later Islam.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The modern state of Afghanistan began with the Durrani Empire in the 18th century under Ahmad Shah Durrani, although Dost Mohammad Khan is sometimes considered to be the founder of the first modern Afghan state.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan became a buffer state in the Great Game between the British Empire and the Russian Empire.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] From India, the British attempted to subjugate Afghanistan but were repelled in the First Anglo-Afghan War; the Second Anglo-Afghan War saw a British victory.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Following the Third Anglo-Afghan War in 1919, Afghanistan became free of foreign political hegemony, and emerged as the independent Kingdom of Afghanistan in 1926; this monarchy lasted almost half a century.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Since the late 1970s, Afghanistan's history has been dominated by extensive warfare, including coups, invasions, insurgencies, and civil wars.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] This period of instability began in 1973 when King Zahir Shah was overthrown by his cousin Mohammad Daoud Khan, ending the monarchy and resulting in the establishment of the Republic of Afghanistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Daoud Khan became the President of Afghanistan, ruling as an autocrat.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] In 1978 the conflict became a violent one when a communist revolution overthrew and assassinated Daoud Khan, establishing the socialist Democratic Republic of Afghanistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Subsequent infighting prompted the Soviet Union to invade Afghanistan in 1979.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The *mujahideen* won against the Soviets in the Soviet–Afghan War, leading to the Soviets' withdrawal in 1989.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The ensuing civil war overthrew the socialist republic and established the Islamic State of Afghanistan through the Peshawar Accord, which could not remain in force and resulted in a second civil war between *mujahideen* factions in 1992.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban controlled most of the country by 1996, but their Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan received little international recognition before its overthrow in the 2001 US invasion of Afghanistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban returned to power in 2021 after capturing Kabul, ending the 2001–2021 war.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban government is widely unrecognized by the international community due to reported violations of human rights in Afghanistan, particularly regarding the treatment of women by the Taliban.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan is rich in natural resources, including lithium, iron, zinc, and copper.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] It is the third largest producer of both saffron and cashmere.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The country is a member of the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation and a founding member of the Organization of Islamic Cooperation.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Due to the effects of war in recent decades, the country has dealt with high levels of terrorism, poverty, and child malnutrition.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan remains among the world's least developed countries with its economic output per capita among the lowest of any country.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Some scholars suggest that the root name *Afghān* is derived from the Sanskrit word *Aśvakan*, which was the name used for ancient inhabitants of the Hindu Kush.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] *Aśvakan* literally means "horsemen", "horse breeders", or "cavalrymen" (from *aśva*, the Sanskrit and Avestan words for "horse").
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Historically, the ethnonym *Afghān* was used to refer to ethnic Pashtuns.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The Arabic and Persian form of the name, *Afġān*, was first attested in the 10th-century geography book *Hudud al-'Alam*.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The last part of the name, "*-stan*", is a Persian suffix meaning "place of".
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Therefore, "Afghanistan" translates to "land of the Afghans", or "land of the Pashtuns" in a historical sense.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The term "Afghanistan" was officially used in 1855, when the British recognized Dost Mohammad Khan as king of Afghanistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Excavations of prehistoric sites suggest that humans were living in what is now Afghanistan at least 50,000 years ago, and that farming communities in the area were among the earliest in the world.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] An important site of early historical activities, many believe that Afghanistan compares to Egypt in the historical value of its archaeological sites.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Artifacts typical of the Paleolithic, Mesolithic, Neolithic, Bronze, and Iron Ages have been found in Afghanistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Urban civilization is believed to have begun as early as 3000 BCE, and the early city of Mundigak (near Kandahar in the south of the country) was a center of the Helmand culture.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] More recent findings established that the Indus Valley Civilization stretched up towards modern-day Afghanistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] An Indus Valley site has been found on the Oxus River at Shortugai in northern Afghanistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] After 2000 BCE successive waves of semi-nomadic people from Central Asia began moving south into Afghanistan; among them were many Indo-European-speaking Indo-Iranians.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] These tribes later migrated further into South Asia, Western Asia, and toward Europe via the area north of the Caspian Sea.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The region at the time was referred to as Ariana.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] By the middle of the 6th century BCE, the Achaemenids overthrew the Medes and incorporated Arachosia, Aria, and Bactria within its eastern boundaries.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] An inscription on the tombstone of Darius I of Persia mentions the Kabul Valley in a list of the 29 countries that he had conquered.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The region of Arachosia, around Kandahar in modern-day southern Afghanistan, used to be primarily Zoroastrian and played a key role in the transfer of the Avesta to Persia and is thus considered by some to be the "second homeland of Zoroastrianism".
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Alexander the Great and his Macedonian forces arrived in Afghanistan in 330 BCE after defeating Darius III of Persia a year earlier in the Battle of Gaugamela.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Following Alexander's brief occupation, the successor state of the Seleucid Empire controlled the region until 305 BCE, when they gave much of it to the Maurya Empire as part of an alliance treaty.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The Mauryans controlled the area south of the Hindu Kush until they were overthrown in about 185 BCE.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Their decline began 60 years after Ashoka's rule ended, leading to the Hellenistic reconquest by the Greco-Bactrians.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Much of it soon broke away and became part of the Indo-Greek Kingdom.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] They were defeated and expelled by the Indo-Scythians in the late 2nd century BCE.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The Silk Road appeared during the first century BCE, and Afghanistan flourished with trade, with routes to China, India, Persia, and north to the cities of Bukhara, Samarkand, and Khiva in present-day Uzbekistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Goods and ideas were exchanged at this center point, such as Chinese silk, Persian silver and Roman gold, while the region of present Afghanistan was mining and trading lapis lazuli stones mainly from the Badakhshan region.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] During the first century BCE, the Parthian Empire subjugated the region but lost it to their Indo-Parthian vassals.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] In the mid-to-late first century CE the vast Kushan Empire, centered in Afghanistan, became great patrons of Buddhist culture, making Buddhism flourish throughout the region.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The Kushans were overthrown by the Sassanids in the 3rd century CE, though the Indo-Sassanids continued to rule at least parts of the region.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] They were followed by the Kidarites who, in turn, was replaced by the Hephthalites.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] They were replaced by the Turk Shahi in the 7th century.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The Buddhist Turk Shahi of Kabul was replaced by a Hindu dynasty before the Saffarids conquered the area in 870; this Hindu dynasty was called Hindu Shahi.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Much of the northeastern and southern areas of the country remained dominated by Buddhist culture.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Arab Muslims brought Islam to Herat and Zaranj in 642 CE and began spreading eastward; some of the native inhabitants they encountered accepted it while others revolted.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Before the arrival of Islam, the region used to be home to various beliefs and cults, often resulting in Syncretism between the dominant religions such as Zoroastrianism, Buddhism or Greco-Buddhism, Ancient Iranian religions, Hinduism, Christianity, and Judaism.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] An exemplification of the syncretism in the region would be that people were patrons of Buddhism but still worshipped local Iranian gods such as Ahura Mazda, Lady Nana, Anahita or Mihr (Mithra) and portrayed Greek gods as protectors of Buddha.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The Zunbils and Kabul Shahi were first conquered in 870 CE by the Saffarid Muslims of Zaranj.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Later, the Samanids extended their Islamic influence south of the Hindu Kush.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The Ghaznavids rose to power in the 10th century.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] By the 11th century, Mahmud of Ghazni had defeated the remaining Hindu rulers and effectively Islamized the wider region, with the exception of Kafiristan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Mahmud made Ghazni into an important city and patronized intellectuals such as the historian al-Biruni and the poet Ferdowsi.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The Ghaznavid dynasty was overthrown by the Ghurids in 1186, whose architectural achievements included the remote Minaret of Jam.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The Ghurids controlled Afghanistan for less than a century before being conquered by the Khwarazmian dynasty in 1215.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] In 1219 CE, Genghis Khan and his Mongol army overran the region.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] His troops are said to have annihilated the Khwarazmian cities of Herat and Balkh as well as Bamyan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The destruction caused by the Mongols forced many locals to return to an agrarian rural society.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Mongol rule continued with the Ilkhanate in the northwest while the Khalji dynasty administered the Afghan tribal areas south of the Hindu Kush until the invasion of Timur (aka Tamerlane), who established the Timurid Empire in 1370.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Under the rule of Shah Rukh, the city of Herat served as the focal point of the Timurid Renaissance, whose glory matched Florence of the Italian Renaissance as the center of a cultural rebirth.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] In the early 16th century Babur arrived from Ferghana and captured Kabul from the Arghun dynasty.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Babur would go on to conquer the Afghan Lodi dynasty who had ruled the Delhi Sultanate in the First Battle of Panipat.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Between the 16th and 18th century, the Uzbek Khanate of Bukhara, Iranian Safavids, and Indian Mughals ruled parts of the territory.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] During the medieval period, the northwestern area of Afghanistan was referred to by the regional name Khorasan, which was commonly used up to the 19th century among natives to describe their country.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] In 1709, Mirwais Hotak, a local Ghilzai tribal leader, successfully rebelled against the Safavids.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] He defeated Gurgin Khan, the Georgian governor of Kandahar under the Safavids, and established his own kingdom.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Mirwais died in 1715, and was succeeded by his brother Abdul Aziz, who was soon killed by Mirwais's son Mahmud for possibly planning to sign a peace with the Safavids.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Mahmud led the Afghan army in 1722 to the Persian capital of Isfahan, and captured the city after the Battle of Gulnabad and proclaimed himself King of Persia.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The Afghan dynasty was ousted from Persia by Nader Shah after the 1729 Battle of Damghan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] In 1738, Nader Shah and his forces captured Kandahar in the siege of Kandahar, the last Hotak stronghold, from Shah Hussain Hotak.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Soon after, the Persian and Afghan forces invaded India, Nader Shah had plundered Delhi, alongside his 16-year-old commander, Ahmad Shah Durrani who had assisted him on these campaigns.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Ahmad Shah had launched two campaigns into Khorasan, 1750–1751 and 1754–1755.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] By the early 19th century, the Afghan empire was under threat from the Persians in the west and the Sikh Empire in the east.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Fateh Khan, leader of the Barakzai tribe, installed many of his brothers in positions of power throughout the empire.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Fateh Khan was brutally murdered in 1818 by Mahmud Shah.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] As a result, the brothers of Fateh Khan and the Barakzai tribe rebelled, and a civil war brewed.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] During this turbulent period, Afghanistan fractured into many states, including the Principality of Qandahar, Emirate of Herat, Khanate of Qunduz, Maimana Khanate, and numerous other warring polities.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The most prominent state was the Emirate of Kabul, ruled by Dost Mohammad Khan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Akbar Khan and the Afghan army failed to capture the Jamrud Fort from the Sikh Khalsa Army, but killed Sikh commander Hari Singh Nalwa, thus ending the Afghan-Sikh Wars.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] In 1893, Abdur Rahman signed an agreement in which the ethnic Pashtun and Baloch territories were divided by the Durand Line, which forms the modern-day border between Pakistan and Afghanistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Shia-dominated Hazarajat and pagan Kafiristan remained politically independent until being conquered by Abdur Rahman Khan in 1891–1896.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] He was known as the "Iron Amir" for his features and his ruthless methods against tribes.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] He died in 1901, succeeded by his son, Habibullah Khan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] During the First World War, when Afghanistan was neutral, Habibullah Khan was met by officials of the Central Powers in the Niedermayer–Hentig Expedition.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] They called on Afghanistan to declare full independence from the United Kingdom, join them and attack British India, as part of the Hindu–German Conspiracy.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The effort to bring Afghanistan into the Central Powers failed, but it sparked discontent among the population about maintaining neutrality with the British.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Habibullah was assassinated in February 1919, and Amanullah Khan eventually assumed power.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] A staunch supporter of the 1915–1916 expeditions, Amanullah Khan invaded British India, beginning the Third Anglo-Afghan War, and entering British India via the Khyber Pass.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Following the end of the Third Anglo-Afghan War and the signing of the Treaty of Rawalpindi on 19 August 1919, Emir Amanullah Khan declared the Emirate of Afghanistan a sovereign and fully independent state.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] He moved to end his country's traditional isolation by establishing diplomatic relations with the international community, particularly with the Soviet Union and the Weimar Republic.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] He proclaimed himself King of Afghanistan on 9 June 1926, forming the Kingdom of Afghanistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] He introduced several reforms intended to modernize his nation.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] A key force behind these reforms was Mahmud Tarzi, an ardent supporter of the education of women.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] He fought for Article 68 of Afghanistan's 1923 constitution, which implemented compulsory elementary education.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] King Amanullah's wife, Queen Soraya, was an important figure during this period in the fight for women's education and against their oppression.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Some of the reforms, such as the abolition of the traditional burqa for women and the opening of co-educational schools, alienated many tribal and religious leaders, leading to the Afghan Civil War (1928–1929).
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] King Amanullah abdicated in January 1929, and soon after Kabul fell to Saqqawist forces led by Habibullah Kalakani.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Mohammad Nadir Shah, Amanullah's cousin, defeated and killed Kalakani in October 1929, and was declared King Nadir Shah.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] He abandoned the reforms of King Amanullah in favor of a more gradual approach to modernization, but was assassinated in 1933 by Abdul Khaliq.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Mohammed Zahir Shah succeeded to the throne and reigned as king from 1933 to 1973.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] During the tribal revolts of 1944–1947, King Zahir's reign was challenged by Zadran, Safi, Mangal, and Wazir tribesmen led by Mazrak Zadran, Salemai, and Faqir of Ipi, among others – many of whom were Amanullah loyalists.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan joined the League of Nations in 1934.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] In the 1930s, the country experienced significant development of roads, infrastructure, the founding of a national bank, and increased education.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Road links in the north played a large part in a growing cotton and textile industry.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The country built close relationships with the Axis powers, with Nazi Germany having the largest share in Afghan development at the time.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Until 1946, King Zahir ruled with the assistance of his uncle, who held the post of prime minister and continued the policies of Nadir Shah.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Another uncle, Shah Mahmud Khan, became prime minister in 1946 and experimented with allowing greater political freedom.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] He was replaced in 1953 by Mohammed Daoud Khan, a Pashtun nationalist who sought the creation of a Pashtunistan, leading to highly tense relations with Pakistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Daoud Khan pressed for social modernization reforms and sought a closer relationship with the Soviet Union.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Afterward, the 1964 constitution was formed, and the first non-royal prime minister was sworn in.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Zahir Shah, like his father Nadir Shah, had a policy of maintaining national independence while pursuing gradual modernization, creating nationalist feeling, and improving relations with the United Kingdom.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan was neither a participant in World War II nor aligned with either power bloc in the Cold War.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] However, it was a beneficiary of the latter rivalry as both the Soviet Union and the United States vied for influence by building Afghanistan's main highways, airports, and other vital infrastructure.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] On a per capita basis, Afghanistan received more Soviet development aid than any other country.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] In 1973, while the King was in Italy, Daoud Khan launched a bloodless coup and became the first president of Afghanistan, abolishing the monarchy.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] In April 1978, the communist People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan (PDPA) seized power in a bloody coup d'état against then-President Mohammed Daoud Khan, in what is called the Saur Revolution.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The PDPA declared the establishment of the Democratic Republic of Afghanistan, with its first leader named as People's Democratic Party General Secretary Nur Muhammad Taraki.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] This would trigger a series of events that would dramatically turn Afghanistan from a peaceful (albeit poor and secluded) country to a hotbed of conflict and terrorism.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The PDPA initiated various social, symbolic, and land distribution reforms that provoked strong opposition, while also brutally oppressing political dissidents.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] This caused unrest and quickly expanded into a state of civil war by 1979, waged by guerrilla *mujahideen* (and smaller Maoist guerrillas) against regime forces countrywide.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] It quickly turned into a proxy war as the Pakistani government provided these rebels with covert training centers, the United States supported them through Pakistan's Inter-Services Intelligence (ISI), and the Soviet Union sent thousands of military advisers to support the PDPA regime.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Meanwhile, there was increasingly hostile friction between the competing factions of the PDPA – the dominant Khalq and the more moderate Parcham.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] In October 1979, PDPA General Secretary Taraki was assassinated in an internal coup orchestrated by then-prime minister Hafizullah Amin, who became the new general secretary of the PDPA.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The situation in the country deteriorated under Amin, and thousands of people went missing.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Displeased with Amin's government, the Soviet Army invaded the country in December 1979, heading for Kabul and killing Amin.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] A Soviet-organized regime, led by Parcham's Babrak Karmal but inclusive of both factions (Parcham and Khalq), filled the vacuum.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Soviet troops in more substantial numbers were deployed to stabilize Afghanistan under Karmal, marking the beginning of the Soviet–Afghan War.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Lasting nine years, the war caused the deaths of between 562,000 and 2 million Afghans, and displaced about 6 million people who subsequently fled Afghanistan, mainly to Pakistan and Iran.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Heavy air bombardment destroyed many countryside villages, millions of landmines were planted, and some cities such as Herat and Kandahar were also damaged from bombardment.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] After the Soviet withdrawal, another civil war ensued until the communist regime under PDPA leader Mohammad Najibullah collapsed in 1992.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The Soviet–Afghan War had drastic social effects on Afghanistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The militarization of society led to heavily armed police, private bodyguards, openly armed civil defense groups, and the like becoming the norm in Afghanistan for decades thereafter.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The traditional power structure had shifted from the clergy, community elders, intelligentsia, and military in favor of powerful warlords.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Another civil war broke out after the creation of a dysfunctional coalition government between leaders of various *mujahideen* factions.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Amid a state of anarchy and factional infighting, various *mujahideen* factions committed widespread rape, murder, and extortion, while Kabul was heavily bombarded and partially destroyed by the fighting.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Several failed reconciliations and alliances occurred between different leaders.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban emerged in September 1994 as a movement and militia of students (*talib*) from Islamic madrassas (schools) in Pakistan, who soon had military support from Pakistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Taking control of Kandahar city that year, they conquered more territories until finally driving out the government of Rabbani from Kabul in 1996, where they established an emirate.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban were condemned internationally for the harsh enforcement of their interpretation of Islamic sharia law, which resulted in the brutal treatment of many Afghans, especially women.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] During their rule, the Taliban and their allies committed massacres against Afghan civilians, denied UN food supplies to starving civilians, and conducted a policy of scorched earth, burning vast areas of fertile land and destroying tens of thousands of homes.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] After the fall of Kabul to the Taliban, Ahmad Shah Massoud and Abdul Rashid Dostum formed the Northern Alliance, later joined by others, to resist the Taliban.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Dostum's forces were defeated by the Taliban during the Battles of Mazar-i-Sharif in 1997 and 1998; Pakistan's Chief of Army Staff, Pervez Musharraf, began sending thousands of Pakistani militants to help the Taliban defeat the Northern Alliance.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] By 2000, the Northern Alliance only controlled 10% of the territory, cornered in the northeast.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] On 9 September 2001, Massoud was assassinated by two Arab suicide attackers in Panjshir Valley.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Around 400,000 Afghans died in internal conflicts between 1990 and 2001.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] In October 2001, the United States invaded Afghanistan to remove the Taliban from power after they refused to hand over Osama bin Laden, the prime suspect of the September 11 attacks, who was a "guest" of the Taliban and was operating his al-Qaeda network in Afghanistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The majority of Afghans supported the American invasion.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] During the initial invasion, US and UK forces bombed al-Qaeda training camps, and later, in cooperation with the Northern Alliance, the Taliban regime came to an end.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] In December 2001, after the Taliban government was overthrown, the Afghan Interim Administration under Hamid Karzai was formed.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The International Security Assistance Force (ISAF) was established by the United Nations Security Council to assist the Karzai administration and provide basic security.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] By this time, after two decades of war as well as an acute famine at the time, Afghanistan had one of the highest infant and child mortality rates in the world, the lowest life expectancy, much of the population suffered from hunger and malnutrition, and infrastructure was in ruins.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Many foreign donors started providing aid and assistance to rebuild the war-torn country.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] As coalition troops entered Afghanistan to help the rebuilding process, the Taliban began an insurgency to regain control.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan remained one of the poorest countries in the world because of a lack of foreign investment, government corruption, and the Taliban insurgency.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The Afghan government was able to establish some democratic structures, adopting a constitution in 2004 with the name Islamic Republic of Afghanistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Attempts were made, often with the support of foreign donor countries, to improve the country's economy, healthcare, education, transport, and agriculture.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] ISAF forces also began to train the Afghan National Security Forces.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Following 2002, nearly five million Afghans were repatriated.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The number of NATO troops present in Afghanistan peaked at 140,000 in 2011, dropping to approximately 16,000 in 2018.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] In September 2014, Ashraf Ghani became president after the 2014 Afghan presidential election, in which, for the first time in Afghanistan's history, power was democratically transferred.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] On 28 December 2014, NATO formally ended ISAF combat operations and transferred full security responsibility to the Afghan government.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The NATO-led Operation Resolute Support was formed the same day as a successor to ISAF.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Thousands of NATO troops remained in the country to train and advise Afghan government forces and continue their fight against the Taliban.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] A report titled *Body Count* concluded that 106,000–170,000 civilians had been killed as a result of the fighting in Afghanistan at the hands of all parties to the conflict.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] On 19 February 2020, the United States–Taliban deal was made in Qatar.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] NATO Secretary General Jens Stoltenberg announced on 14 April 2021 that the alliance had agreed to start withdrawing its troops from Afghanistan by 1 May.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Soon after NATO troops began withdrawing, the Taliban launched an offensive against the Afghan government and quickly advanced in front of collapsing Afghan government forces.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban captured the capital city of Kabul on 15 August 2021, after regaining control over a vast majority of Afghanistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Several foreign diplomats and Afghan government officials, including President Ashraf Ghani, were evacuated from the country, with many Afghan civilians attempting to flee along with them.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] On 17 August, first vice president Amrullah Saleh proclaimed himself caretaker president and announced the formation of an anti-Taliban front with a reported 6,000+ troops in the Panjshir Valley, along with Ahmad Massoud.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] However, by 6 September, the Taliban had taken control of most of Panjshir Province, with resistance fighters retreating to the mountains.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Clashes in the valley ceased in mid-September.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] According to the Costs of War Project, 176,000 people were killed in the conflict, including 46,319 civilians, between 2001 and 2021.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] According to the Uppsala Conflict Data Program, at least 212,191 people were killed in the conflict.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Though the state of war in the country ended in 2021, armed conflict persists in some regions amid fighting between the Taliban and the local branch of the Islamic State, as well as an anti-Taliban Republican insurgency.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban government is led by supreme leader Hibatullah Akhundzada and acting prime minister Hasan Akhund, who took office on 7 September 2021.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Akhund is one of the four founders of the Taliban and was a deputy prime minister of the previous emirate; his appointment was seen as a compromise between moderates and hardliners.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] A new, all-male cabinet was formed, which included Abdul Hakim Haqqani as minister of justice.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] On 20 September 2021, United Nations Secretary-General António Guterres received a letter from acting minister of foreign affairs Amir Khan Muttaqi to formally claim Afghanistan's seat as a member state for their official spokesman in Doha, Suhail Shaheen.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The United Nations did not recognize the previous Taliban government and chose to work with the then government-in-exile instead.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Western nations suspended most of their humanitarian aid to Afghanistan following the Taliban's August 2021 takeover of the country; the World Bank and International Monetary Fund also halted their payments.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] More than half of Afghanistan's 39 million people faced an acute food shortage in October 2021.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Human Rights Watch reported on 11 November 2021 that Afghanistan was facing widespread famine due to an economic and banking crisis.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban initially significantly tackled corruption, improving on the corruption perceptions index from 174th to 150th out of 180 countries from 2021 to 2022, but dropping to 162nd in 2023.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban have also reportedly reduced bribery and extortion in public service areas.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] At the same time, the human rights situation in the country has deteriorated.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Following the 2001 invasion, more than 5.7 million refugees returned to Afghanistan; however, in 2021, 2.6 million Afghans remained refugees, primarily in Iran and Pakistan, and another 4 million were internally displaced.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] In October 2023, the Pakistani government ordered the expulsion of Afghans from Pakistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Iran also decided to deport Afghan nationals back to Afghanistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Taliban authorities condemned the deportations of Afghans as an "inhuman act".
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan faced a humanitarian crisis in late 2023.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] On 10 November 2024, Afghanistan's Foreign Ministry confirmed that Taliban representatives would attend the 2024 United Nations Climate Change Conference, marking the first time the country participated since the Taliban's return to power in 2021.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan had been barred from previous summits due to the lack of global recognition of the Taliban regime.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] In May 2025, Iran ordered the mass deportation of an estimated 4 million Afghan migrants and refugees.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The 2025–2026 hunger crisis in Afghanistan is one of the world's most severe, with over 17 million people—one-third of the population—requiring urgent food assistance.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Driven by persistent drought, economic collapse, and massive refugee returns, the crisis has left over 4.9 million children and women needing malnutrition treatment.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan is located in Southern-Central Asia.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The region centered in Afghanistan is considered the "crossroads of Asia", and the country has had the nickname Heart of Asia.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] At over 652,864 km2 (252,072 sq mi), Afghanistan is the world's 41st largest country.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] It is slightly bigger than France and smaller than Myanmar, and about the size of Texas in the United States.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] There is no coastline, as Afghanistan is landlocked.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The geography in Afghanistan is varied, but is mostly mountainous and rugged, with some unusual mountain ridges accompanied by plateaus and river basins.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] It is dominated by the Hindu Kush range, the western extension of the Himalayas that stretches to eastern Tibet via the Pamir Mountains and Karakoram Mountains in Afghanistan's far north-east.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Most of the highest points are in the east, consisting of fertile mountain valleys, often considered part of the "Roof of the World".
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The Hindu Kush ends at the west-central highlands, creating plains in the north and southwest, namely the Turkestan Plains and the Sistan Basin; these two regions consist of rolling grasslands and semi-deserts, as well as hot, windy deserts, respectively.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Forests exist in the corridor between the provinces of Nuristan and Paktika (see East Afghan montane conifer forests), and tundra in the northeast.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The country's highest point is Noshaq, at 7,492 m (24,580 ft) above sea level.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The lowest point is located in Jowzjan Province along the Amu River bank, at 258 m (846 ft) above sea level.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Despite having numerous rivers and reservoirs, large parts of the country are dry.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The endorheic Sistan Basin is one of the world's driest regions.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The Amu Darya rises in the north of the Hindu Kush, while the nearby Hari River flows west towards Herat, and the Arghandab River flows from the central region southwards.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] To the south and west of the Hindu Kush flow a number of streams that are tributaries of the Indus River, such as the Helmand River.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The Kabul River flows in an easterly direction to the Indus, ending at the Indian Ocean.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan receives heavy snow during the winter in the Hindu Kush and Pamir Mountains, and the melting snow in the spring season enters the rivers, lakes, and streams.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] However, two-thirds of the country's water flows into the neighboring countries of Iran, Pakistan, and Turkmenistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] As reported in 2010, the state needs more than US$2 billion to rehabilitate its irrigation systems so that the water is properly managed.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] In Afghanistan, forest cover accounts for approximately 2% of the total land area, equivalent to 1,208,440 hectares (ha) of forest in 2020, which remained unchanged since 1990.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Of the naturally regenerating forest, 0% was reported to be primary forest (consisting of native tree species with no clearly visible indications of human activity), and around 0% of the forest area was found within protected areas.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] For the year 2015, 100% of the forest area was reported to be under public ownership.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The northeastern Hindu Kush mountain range, located in and around the Badakhshan Province of Afghanistan, is situated in a geologically active area where earthquakes occur almost every year.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] They can be deadly and destructive, causing landslides in some parts or avalanches during the winter.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] In June 2022, a destructive 5.9 earthquake struck near the border with Pakistan, killing at least 1,150 people and sparking fears of a major humanitarian crisis.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] On 7 October 2023, a 6.3 magnitude earthquake struck northwest of Herat, killing over 1,400 people.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The country is generally arid in the summers, with most rainfall falling between December and April.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The lower areas of northern and western Afghanistan are the driest, with precipitation more common in the east.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Although proximate to India, Afghanistan is mostly outside the monsoon zone, except the Nuristan Province, which occasionally receives summer monsoon rain.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Although Afghanistan has contributed minimally to global greenhouse gas emissions, it is one of the most vulnerable countries to climate change and least prepared to cope with its impacts.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Climate change in Afghanistan is causing more frequent and severe droughts.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Severe drought conditions affect 25 of the country's 34 provinces, impacting over half the population.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] These droughts cause desertification, reduce food and water security, disrupt agriculture, and cause internal displacement.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Extreme rainfall over short periods is also more likely, increasing the risk of floods and landslides.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Due to rising temperatures, almost 14% of Afghanistan's glacier coverage was lost between 1990 and 2015, increasing the risk of glacial lake outburst floods.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] By 2050, climate change could displace an additional 5 million people within Afghanistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Several types of mammals exist throughout Afghanistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Snow leopards and brown bears live in the high elevation alpine tundra regions.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The Marco Polo sheep exclusively live in the Wakhan Corridor region of north-east Afghanistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Foxes, wolves, otters, deer, wild sheep, lynx and other big cats populate the mountain forest region of the east.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] In the semi-desert northern plains, wildlife include a variety of birds, hedgehogs, gophers, and large carnivores such as jackals and hyenas.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Gazelles, wild pigs and jackals populate the steppe plains of the south and west, while mongoose and cheetahs exist in the semi-desert south.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Marmots and ibex also live in the high mountains of Afghanistan, and pheasants exist in some parts of the country.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The Afghan hound is a native breed of dog known for its fast speed and its long hair; it is relatively known in the west.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Endemic fauna of Afghanistan includes the Afghan flying squirrel, Afghan snowfinch, *Paradactylodon* (or the "Paghman mountain salamander"), *Stigmella kasyi*, *Vulcaniella kabulensis*, Afghan leopard gecko, *Wheeleria parviflorellus*, among others.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan has a wide variety of birds despite its relatively arid climate – an estimated 460 species of which 235 breed within.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The forest region of Afghanistan has vegetation such as pine trees, spruce trees, fir trees and larches, whereas the steppe grassland regions consist of broadleaf trees, short grass, perennial plants and shrublands.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] The colder high elevation regions are composed of hardy grasses and small flowering plants.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Several regions are designated protected areas; there are three national parks: Band-e Amir, Wakhan and Nuristan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan had a 2018 Forest Landscape Integrity Index mean score of 8.85/10, ranking it 15th globally out of 172 countries.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Following the effective collapse of the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan during the 2021 Taliban offensive, the Taliban declared the country an Islamic Emirate.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] A new caretaker government was announced on 7 September.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] As of July 2025, only the Russian Federation has recognized the Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan as the *de jure* government of Afghanistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] In the V-Dem Democracy Indices, Afghanistan ranks amongst the lowest as a "closed autocracy," ranking at 176th and 177th out of 179 countries in electoral democracy and liberal democracy indices respectively.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan operates on a centralised unitary form of government.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] A traditional instrument of governance in Afghanistan is the *loya jirga* (grand assembly), a Pashtun consultative meeting that was mainly organized for choosing a new head of state, adopting a new constitution, or to settle national or regional issue such as war.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Loya jirgas have been held since at least 1747, with the most recent one occurring from June to July 2022.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] President Ashraf Ghani, having fled the country during the Taliban advance to either Tajikistan or Uzbekistan, emerged in the United Arab Emirates and said that he supported such negotiations and was in talks to return to Afghanistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Many figures within the Taliban generally agreed that continuation of the 2004 Constitution of Afghanistan may, if correctly applied, be workable as the basis for the new religious state as their objections to the former government were political, and not religious.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Hours after the final flight of American troops left Kabul on 30 August, a Taliban official interviewed said that a new government would likely be announced as early as Friday 3 September after Jumu'ah.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] It was added that Hibatullah Akhundzada would be officially named Emir, with cabinet ministers being revealed at the Arg in an official ceremony.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Abdul Ghani Baradar would be named head of government as Prime Minister, while other important positions would go to Sirajuddin Haqqani and Mullah Yaqoob.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Beneath the supreme leader, day-to-day governance will be entrusted to the cabinet.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] In a report by CNN-News18, sources said the new government was going to be governed similarly to Iran with Hibatullah Akhundzada as supreme leader similar to the role of Saayid Ali Khamenei, and would be based out of Kandahar.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Baradar or Yaqoob would be head of government as Prime minister.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The government's ministries and agencies will be under a cabinet presided over by the Prime Minister.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The Supreme Leader would preside over an executive body known as the Supreme Council with anywhere from 11 to 72 members.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Abdul Hakim Haqqani is likely to be promoted to Chief justice.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] According to the report, the new government will take place within the framework of an amended 1964 Constitution of Afghanistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Government formation was delayed due to concerns about forming a broad-based government acceptable to the international community.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] It was later added however that the Taliban's Rahbari Shura, the group's leadership council was divided between the hardline Haqqani Network and moderate Abdul Ghani Baradar over appointments needed to form an "inclusive" government.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Reports claimed that this culminated in a skirmish which led to Baradar being injured and treated in Pakistan, however this was denied by Baradar himself.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] As of early September 2021 the Taliban were planning the cabinet to be men-only.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Journalists and other human rights activists, mostly women, protested in Herat and Kabul, calling for women to be included.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The acting Cabinet announced on 7 September was men-only, and the Ministry of Women's Affairs was abolished.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] As of July 2025, only Russia has recognized the Taliban government as the legitimate authorities of Afghanistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The U.N has stated that recognition was impossible so long as restrictions on female education and employment remained.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] On 16 September 2024, the Taliban suspended polio vaccination campaigns in Afghanistan, as reported by the United Nations, posing a significant risk to global polio eradication efforts.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] In a decree by Hibatullah Akhundzada on 15 August 2025, the description of the government as interim was dropped, with all ministers remaining in their posts, but on a permanent rather than acting basis.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan is administratively divided into 34 provinces (*wilayat*).
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Each province has a governor and a capital.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The country is further divided into nearly 400 provincial districts, each of which normally covers a city or several villages.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Each district is represented by a district governor.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The provincial governors are now appointed by the Prime Minister of Afghanistan, and the district governors are selected by the provincial governors.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The provincial governors are representatives of the central government in Kabul and are responsible for all administrative and formal issues within their provinces.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] There are also provincial councils that are elected through direct and general elections for four years.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The functions of provincial councils are to take part in provincial development planning and to participate in the monitoring and appraisal of other provincial governance institutions.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] According to article 140 of the constitution and the presidential decree on electoral law, mayors of cities should be elected through free and direct elections for a four-year term.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] In practice however, mayors are appointed by the government.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan became a member of the United Nations in 1946.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Relations with Pakistan have often been tense for various reasons such as the Durand Line border issue and alleged Pakistani involvement in Afghan insurgent groups.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The present Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan is currently partially recognized, but has had notable unofficial ties with China, Pakistan, and Qatar.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Under the previous Islamic Republic of Afghanistan, it enjoyed cordial relations with a number of NATO and allied nations, particularly the United States, Canada, United Kingdom, Germany, Australia, and Turkey.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] In 2012, the United States and the then-republic in Afghanistan signed their Strategic Partnership Agreement in which Afghanistan became a major non-NATO ally.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Such qualification was rescinded by US President Joe Biden in July 2022.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The Armed Forces of the Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan captured a large amount of weapons, hardware, vehicles, aerocrafts, and equipment from the Afghan National Security Forces following the 2021 Taliban offensive and the Fall of Kabul.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The total value of the captured equipment has been estimated at US$83 billion.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Homosexuality is taboo in Afghan society; according to the Penal Code, homosexual intimacy is punished by up to a year in prison.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Under Sharia law offenders can be punished by death.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] However, an ancient tradition involving male homosexual acts between children and older men (typically wealthy warlords or elite people) called *bacha bazi* persists albeit punishable by the death penalty under Taliban law.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Religious minorities such as Sikhs, Hindus, and Christians have reportedly faced persecution.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Since May 2022, all women in Afghanistan have been required by law to wear full-body coverings when in public (either a burqa or an abaya paired with a niqāb, which leaves only the eyes uncovered).
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] First Deputy Leader Sirajuddin Haqqani claimed the decree is only advisory and no form of hijab is compulsory in Afghanistan, though this contradicts the reality.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] It has been speculated that there is a genuine internal policy division over women's rights between hardliners, including leader Hibatullah Akhundzada, and pragmatists, though they publicly present a united front.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Another decree was issued shortly after the first, requiring female TV presenters to cover their faces during broadcasts.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Since the Taliban takeover, suicides among women have become more common, and the country could now be one of the few where the rate of suicide among women surpasses that among men.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] In May 2022, the Taliban dissolved Afghanistan's Human Rights Commission along with four other government departments, citing the country's budget deficit.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] ICC member states are obliged to arrest wanted persons if they are on their territory.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan's nominal GDP was $20.1 billion in 2020, or $81 billion by purchasing power parity (PPP).
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Its GDP per capita is $2,459 (PPP) and $611 by nominal.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Despite having $1 trillion or more in mineral deposits, it remains one of the world's least developed countries.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Its economic output per capita is among the lowest of any country as of 2026.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan's rough physical geography and its landlocked status has been cited as reasons why the country has always been among the least developed in the modern era – a factor where progress is also slowed by contemporary conflict and political instability.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The country imports over $7 billion worth of goods but exports only $784 million, mainly fruits and nuts.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The service sector contributed the most to the GDP (55.9%) followed by agriculture (23%) and industry (21.1%).
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Da Afghanistan Bank serves as the central bank of the nation and the Afghani (AFN) is the national currency, with an exchange rate of about 75 Afghanis to 1 US dollar.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] A number of local and foreign banks operate in the country, including the Afghanistan International Bank, New Kabul Bank, Azizi Bank, Pashtany Bank, Standard Chartered Bank, and the First Micro Finance Bank.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] In 2010, one of the main drivers for the economic recovery was the return of over 5 million expatriates, who brought with them entrepreneurship and wealth-creating skills as well as much needed funds to start up businesses.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Many Afghans got involved in construction, which was one of the largest industries in the country at the time.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Some of the major national construction projects include the $35 billion New Kabul City next to the capital, the Aino Mena project in Kandahar, and the Ghazi Amanullah Khan Town near Jalalabad.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Similar development projects have also begun in Herat, Mazar-e-Sharif, and other cities.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] An estimated 400,000 people enter the labor market each year.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Several small companies and factories began operating in different parts of the country, which not only provide revenues to the government but also create new jobs.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Improvements to the business environment have resulted in more than $1.5 billion in telecom investment and created more than 100,000 jobs since 2003.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Afghan rugs are becoming popular again, allowing many carpet dealers around the country to hire more workers; in 2016–17 it was the fourth most exported group of items.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan is a member of WTO, SAARC, ECO, and OIC.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] In 2018, a majority of imports come from either Iran, China, Pakistan and Kazakhstan, while 84% of exports are to Pakistan and India.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Since the Taliban's takeover of the country in August 2021, the United States has frozen about $9 billion in assets belonging to the Afghan central bank, blocking the Taliban from accessing billions of dollars held in US bank accounts.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The GDP of Afghanistan is estimated to have dropped by 20% following the Taliban return to power.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Following this, after months of free-fall, the Afghan economy began stabilizing, as a result of the Taliban's restrictions on smuggled imports, limits on banking transactions, and UN aid.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] In 2023, the Afghan economy began seeing signs of revival.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] This has also been followed by stable exchange rates, low inflation, stable revenue collection, and the rise of trade in exports.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] In the third quarter of 2023, the Afghani rose to be the best performing currency in the world, climbing over 9% against the US dollar.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Agricultural production is the backbone of Afghanistan's economy and has traditionally dominated the economy, employing about 40% of the workforce as of 2018.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The country is known for producing pomegranates, grapes, apricots, melons, and several other fresh and dry fruits.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan also became the world's top producer of cannabis in 2010.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] In March 2023, however, cannabis production was banned by a decree from Hibatullah Akhundzada.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Saffron, the most expensive spice, grows in Afghanistan, particularly Herat Province.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] In recent years, there has been an uptick in saffron production, which authorities and farmers are using to try to replace poppy cultivation.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Between 2012 and 2019, the saffron cultivated and produced in Afghanistan was consecutively ranked the world's best by the International Taste and Quality Institute.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Production hit record high in 2019 (19,469 kg of saffron), and one kilogram is sold domestically between $634 and $1147.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The availability of cheap diesel-powered water pumps imported from China and Pakistan, and in the 2010s, of cheap solar power to pump water, resulted in expansion of agriculture and population in the southwestern deserts of Afghanistan in Kandahar, Helmand and Nimruz provinces in the 2010s.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Wells have gradually been deepened, but water resources are limited.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Opium is the major crop, but as of 2022, was under attack by the new Taliban government which, to suppress opium production, was systematically suppressing water pumping.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] In a 2023 report, poppy cultivation in southern Afghanistan was reduced by over 80% as a result of Taliban campaigns to stop its use toward opium.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] This included a 99% reduction of opium growth in the Helmand Province.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] In November 2023, a U.N report showed that in the entirety of Afghanistan, poppy cultivation dropped by over 95%, removing it from its place as being the world's largest opium producer.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The country's natural resources include: coal, copper, iron ore, lithium, uranium, rare earth elements, chromite, gold, zinc, talc, barite, sulfur, lead, marble, precious and semi-precious stones, natural gas, and petroleum.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] In 2010, US and Afghan government officials estimated that untapped mineral deposits located in 2007 by the US Geological Survey are worth at least $1 trillion.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] O'Hanlon of the Brookings Institution estimated that if Afghanistan generates about $10 billion per year from its mineral deposits, its gross national product would double and provide long-term funding for critical needs.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The United States Geological Survey (USGS) estimated in 2006 that northern Afghanistan has an average 460 million m3 (2.9 billion bbl) of crude oil, 440 billion m3 (15.7 trillion cu ft) of natural gas, and 67 billion L (562 million US bbl) of natural gas liquids.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] In 2011, Afghanistan signed an oil exploration contract with China National Petroleum Corporation (CNPC) for the development of three oil fields along the Amu Darya river in the north.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The country has significant amounts of lithium, copper, gold, coal, iron ore, and other minerals.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The Khanashin carbonatite in Helmand Province contains 1,000,000 tonnes (980,000 long tons; 1,100,000 short tons) of rare earth elements.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] In 2007, a 30-year lease was granted for the Aynak copper mine to the China Metallurgical Group for $3 billion, making it the biggest foreign investment and private business venture in Afghanistan's history.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The state-run Steel Authority of India won the mining rights to develop the huge Hajigak iron ore deposit in central Afghanistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Government officials estimate that 30% of the country's untapped mineral deposits are worth at least $1 trillion.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] One official asserted that "this will become the backbone of the Afghan economy" and a Pentagon memo stated that Afghanistan could become the "Saudi Arabia of lithium".
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The lithium reserves of 21 Mio. tons could amount to the ones of Bolivia, which is currently viewed as the country with the largest lithium reserves.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Other larger deposits are the ones of bauxite and cobalt.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Access to biocapacity in Afghanistan is lower than world average.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] In 2016, Afghanistan had 0.43 global hectares of biocapacity per person within its territory, much less than the world average of 1.6 global hectares per person.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] In 2016 Afghanistan used 0.73 global hectares of biocapacity per person—their ecological footprint of consumption.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] This means they use just under double as much biocapacity as Afghanistan contains.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] As a result, Afghanistan is running a biocapacity deficit.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] In September 2023, the Taliban signed mining contracts worth $6.5 billion, with extractions based on gold, iron, lead, and zinc in the provinces of Herat, Ghor, Logar, and Takhar.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] According to the World Bank, 98% of the rural population have access to electricity in 2018, up from 28% in 2008.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] As of 2016, Afghanistan produces 1,400 megawatts of power, but still imports the majority of electricity via transmission lines from Iran and the Central Asian states.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The majority of electricity production is via hydropower, helped by the amount of rivers and streams that flow from the mountains.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] However electricity is not always reliable and blackouts happen, including in Kabul.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] In recent years an increasing number of solar, biomass and wind power plants have been constructed.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Currently under development are the CASA-1000 project which will transmit electricity from Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan, and the Turkmenistan-Afghanistan-Pakistan-India (TAPI) gas pipeline.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Power is managed by the Da Afghanistan Breshna Sherkat (DABS, Afghanistan Electricity Company).
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Important dams include the Kajaki Dam, Dahla Dam, and the Sardeh Band Dam.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Tourism is a small industry in Afghanistan due to security issues.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Nevertheless, some 20,000 foreign tourists visit the country annually as of 2016.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] In particular an important region for domestic and international tourism is the picturesque Bamyan Valley, which includes lakes, canyons and historical sites, helped by the fact it is in a safe area away from insurgent activity.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Smaller numbers visit and trek in regions such as the Wakhan Valley, which is also one of the world's most remote communities.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] From the late 1960s onwards, Afghanistan was a popular stop on the famous hippie trail, attracting many Europeans and Americans.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Coming from Iran, the trail traveled through various Afghan provinces and cities including Herat, Kandahar and Kabul before crossing to northern Pakistan, northern India, and Nepal.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Tourism peaked in 1977, the year before the start of political instability and armed conflict.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The city of Ghazni has significant history and historical sites, and together with Bamyan city have in recent years been voted Islamic Cultural Capital and South Asia Cultural Capital respectively.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The cities of Herat, Kandahar, Balkh, and Zaranj are also very historic.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The Minaret of Jam in the Hari River valley is a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] A cloak reputedly worn by Islam's prophet Muhammad is kept in the Shrine of the Cloak in Kandahar, a city founded by Alexander the Great and the first capital of Afghanistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The citadel of Alexander in the western city of Herat has been renovated in recent years and is a popular attraction.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] In the north of the country is the Shrine of Ali, believed by many to be the location where Ali was buried.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The National Museum of Afghanistan in Kabul hosts a large number of Buddhist, Bactrian Greek and early Islamic antiquities; the museum suffered greatly by civil war but has been slowly restoring since the early 2000s.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Unexpectedly, tourism has seen improvement in Afghanistan following the Taliban takeover.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Active efforts by the Taliban encouraged tourism to increase from 691 tourists in 2021, to 2,300 in 2022, to 5,200 in 2023, with some estimates of between 7,000 and 10,000.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] This is, however, threatened by the Islamic State – Khorasan Province, who took responsibility for attacks on tourists, such as the 2024 Bamyan shooting.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Telecommunication services in Afghanistan are provided by Afghan Telecom, Afghan Wireless, Etisalat, MTN Group, and Roshan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The country uses its own space satellite called Afghansat 1, which provides services to millions of phone, internet, and television subscribers.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] By 2001 following years of civil war, telecommunications was virtually a non-existent sector, but by 2016 it had grown to a $2 billion industry, with 22 million mobile phone subscribers and 5 million internet users.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The sector employs at least 120,000 people nationwide.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Due to Afghanistan's geography, transport between various parts of the country has historically been difficult.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The Ring Road is crucially important for domestic and international trade and the economy.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] A key portion of the Ring Road is the Salang Tunnel, completed in 1964, which facilitates travel through the Hindu Kush mountain range and connects northern and southern Afghanistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] It is the only land route that connects Central Asia to the Indian subcontinent.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Several mountain passes allow travel between the Hindu Kush in other areas.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Serious traffic accidents are common on Afghan roads and highways, particularly on the Kabul–Kandahar and the Kabul–Jalalabad Road.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Traveling by bus in Afghanistan remains dangerous due to militant activities.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Air transport in Afghanistan is provided by the national carrier, Ariana Afghan Airlines, and by the private company Kam Air.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Airlines from a number of countries also provide flights in and out of the country.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] These include Air India, Emirates, Gulf Air, Iran Aseman Airlines, Pakistan International Airlines, and Turkish Airlines.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The country has four international airports: Kabul International Airport (formerly Hamid Karzai International Airport), Kandahar International Airport, Herat International Airport, and Mazar-e Sharif International Airport.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Including domestic airports, there are 43.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Bagram Air Base is a major military airfield.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] These lines are used for freight only and there is no passenger service.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] A rail line between Khaf, Iran and Herat, western Afghanistan, intended for both freight and passengers, was under construction as of 2019.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] About 125 kilometres (78 mi) of the line will lie on the Afghan side.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Private vehicle ownership has increased substantially since the early 2000s.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Taxis are yellow and consist of both cars and auto rickshaws.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] In rural Afghanistan, villagers often use donkeys, mules or horses to transport or carry goods.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Camels are primarily used by the Kochi nomads.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Bicycles are popular throughout Afghanistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The population of Afghanistan was estimated at 35.7 million as of 2024 by the Afghanistan National Statistics and Information Authority, whereas the UN estimates over 42.0 million.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] In 1979 the total population was reported to be about 15.5 million.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] About 25.3% are urbanite, 70.4% live in rural areas, and the remaining 4.3% are nomadic.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] An additional 3 million or so Afghans are temporarily housed in neighboring Pakistan and Iran, most of whom were born and raised in those two countries.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] As of 2013, Afghanistan was the largest refugee-producing country in the world, a title held for 32 years.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The current population growth rate is 2.37%, one of the highest in the world outside of Africa.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] This population is expected to reach 82 million by 2050 if current population trends continue.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The population of Afghanistan increased steadily until the 1980s, when civil war caused millions to flee to other countries such as Pakistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Millions have since returned and the war conditions contribute to the country having the highest fertility rate outside Africa.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan's healthcare has recovered since the turn of the century, causing falls in infant mortality and increases in life expectancy, although it has the lowest life expectance of any country outside Africa.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] This (along with other factors such as returning refugees) caused rapid population growth in the 2000s that has only recently started to slow down.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan 2024 total fertility rate has been estimated at 4.4.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] In 2022 it was 4.5, about twice the world average rate.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The rate has fallen since the early 1980s.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] As estimated by the CIA World Factbook, 26% of the population was urbanized as of 2020.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] This is one of the lowest figures in the world; in Asia it is only higher than Cambodia, Nepal and Sri Lanka.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Urbanization has increased rapidly, particularly in the capital Kabul, due to returning refugees from Pakistan and Iran after 2001, internally displaced people, and rural migrants.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Urbanization in Afghanistan is different from typical urbanization in that it is centered on just a few cities.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Kabul is the largest city, with a population of 5 million.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The other large cities are located generally in the "ring" around the Central Highlands, namely Kandahar in the south, Herat in the west, Mazar-i-Sharif, Kunduz in the north, and Jalalabad in the east.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Afghans are divided into several ethnolinguistic groups.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] According to research data by several institutions in 2019, the Pashtuns are the largest ethnic group, comprising 42%, followed by Tajiks, comprising 27% of the country's population.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The other two major ethnic groups are the Hazaras and Uzbeks, each at 9%.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] A further 10 other ethnic groups are recognized and each are represented in the Afghan National Anthem.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Dari and Pashto are the official languages of Afghanistan; bilingualism is very common.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Dari, which is also referred to as Eastern Persian as it is a variety of and mutually intelligible with Persian (and very often called 'Farsi' by some Afghans like in Iran), functions as the lingua franca in Kabul as well as in much of the northern and northwestern parts of the country.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Native speakers of Dari, of any ethnicity, are sometimes called Farsiwans.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Pashto is the native tongue of the Pashtuns, although many of them are also fluent in Dari while some non-Pashtuns are fluent in Pashto.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Despite the Pashtuns having been dominant in Afghan politics for centuries, Dari remained the preferred language for government and bureaucracy.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] According to CIA World Factbook, Dari Persian is spoken by 78% (L1 + L2) and functions as the lingua franca, while Pashto is spoken by 50%, Uzbek 10%, English 5%, Turkmen 2%, Urdu 2%, Pashayi 1%, Nuristani 1%, Arabic 1%, and Balochi 1% (2021 est).
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Data represent the most widely spoken languages; shares sum to more than 100% because there is much bilingualism in the country and because respondents were allowed to select more than one language.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] There are a number of smaller regional languages, including Uzbek, Turkmen, Balochi, Pashayi, and Nuristani.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] When it comes to foreign languages among the populace, many are able to speak or understand Hindustani (Urdu-Hindi), partly due to returning Afghan refugees from Pakistan and the popularity of Bollywood films respectively.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] English is also understood by some of the population, and has been gaining popularity as of the 2000s.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Some Afghans retain some ability in Russian, which was taught in public schools during the 1980s.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The CIA estimated in 2009 that 99.7% of the Afghan population was Muslim and most are thought to adhere to the Sunni Hanafi school.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] According to Pew Research Center, as much as 90% are of the Sunni denomination, 7% Shia and 3% non-denominational.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Conversion away from Islam is persecuted, limiting religious freedom.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Afghan Sikhs and Hindus are also found in certain major cities (namely Kabul, Jalalabad, Ghazni, Kandahar) accompanied by gurdwaras and mandirs.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] According to Deutsche Welle in September 2021, 250 remain in the country after 67 were evacuated to India.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] There was a small Jewish community in Afghanistan, living mainly in Herat and Kabul.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Over the years, this small community was forced to leave due to decades of warfare and religious persecution.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] By the end of the twentieth century, nearly the entire community had emigrated to Israel and the United States, with one known exception, Herat-born Zablon Simintov.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] He remained for years, being the caretaker of the only remaining Afghan synagogue.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] He left the country for the US after the second Taliban takeover.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] A woman who left shortly after him has since been identified as the likely last Jew in Afghanistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Afghan Christians, who number 500–8,000, practice their faith secretly due to intense societal opposition, and there are no public churches.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Education in Afghanistan is overseen by the Ministry of Education and the Ministry of Higher Education.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] There are over 16,000 schools in the country and roughly 9 million students.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Of this, about 60% are males and 40% females.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] However, the new regime has thus far forbidden female teachers and female students from returning to secondary schools.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Over 174,000 students are enrolled in different universities around the country.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Former Education Minister Ghulam Farooq Wardak had stated that construction of 8,000 schools is required for the remaining children who are deprived of formal learning.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] As of 2018 the literacy rate of the population age 15 and older is 43.02% (males 55.48% and females 29.81%).
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The top universities in Afghanistan are the American University of Afghanistan (AUAF) followed by Kabul University (KU), both of which are located in Kabul.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The National Military Academy of Afghanistan, modeled after the United States Military Academy at West Point, was a four-year military development institution dedicated to graduating officers for the Afghan Armed Forces.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The Afghan Defense University was constructed near Qargha in Kabul.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Major universities outside of Kabul include Kandahar University in the south, Herat University in the northwest, Balkh University and Kunduz University in the north, Nangarhar University and Khost University in the east.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] After the Taliban regained power in 2021, it became unclear to what extent female education would continue in the country.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] In March 2022, after they had been closed for some time, it was announced that secondary education would be reopened shortly.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] However, shortly before reopening, the order was rescinded and schools for older girls remained closed.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Despite the ban, six provinces, Balkh, Kunduz, Jowzjan, Sar-I-Pul, Faryab, and the Day Kundi, still allow girls' schools from grade 6 and up.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] In December 2023, investigations were being held by the United Nations on the claim that Afghan girls of all ages were allowed to study at religious schools.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] As of November 2024, some parts of the country allow women to attend religious schools to pursue dentistry, nursing, and other subjects.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] According to the Human Development Index, Afghanistan is the 15th least developed country in the world.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The average life expectancy is estimated to be around 60 years.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The country's maternal mortality rate is 396 deaths/100,000 live births and its infant mortality rate is 66 to 112.8 deaths in every 1,000 live births.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The Ministry of Public Health plans to cut the infant mortality rate to 400 for every 100,000 live births before 2020.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The country has more than 3,000 midwives, with an additional 300 to 400 being trained each year.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] There are over 100 hospitals in Afghanistan, with the most advanced treatments being available in Kabul.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The French Medical Institute for Children and Indira Gandhi Children's Hospital in Kabul are the leading children's hospitals in the country.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Some of the other leading hospitals in Kabul include the Jamhuriat Hospital and Jinnah Hospital.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] In spite of all this, many Afghans travel to Pakistan and India for advanced treatment.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] It was reported in 2006 that nearly 60% of the Afghan population lives within a two-hour walk of the nearest health facility.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] The disability rate is also high in Afghanistan due to the decades of war.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] It was reported recently that about 80,000 people are missing limbs.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p02] Non-governmental charities such as Save the Children and Mahboba's Promise assist orphans in association with governmental structures.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Afghans have both common cultural features and those that differ between the regions of Afghanistan, each with distinctive cultures partly as a result of geographic obstacles that divide the country.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Family is the mainstay of Afghan society and families are often headed by a patriarch.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] In the southern and eastern region, the people live according to the Pashtun culture by following Pashtunwali (the Pashtun way).
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Key tenets of Pashtunwali include hospitality, the provision of sanctuary to those seeking refuge, and revenge for the shedding of blood.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] The Pashtuns are largely connected to the culture of Central Asia and the Iranian Plateau.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] The remaining Afghans are culturally Persian and Turkic.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Some non-Pashtuns who live in proximity with Pashtuns have adopted Pashtunwali in a process called Pashtunization, while some Pashtuns have been Persianized.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Those who have lived in Pakistan and Iran over the last 30 years have been further influenced by the cultures of those neighboring nations.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] The Afghan people are known to be strongly religious.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Afghans, particularly Pashtuns, are noted for their tribal solidarity and high regard for personal honor.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] There are various Afghan tribes, and an estimated 2–3 million nomads.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Afghan culture is deeply Islamic, but pre-Islamic practices persist.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Child marriage is prevalent; in 2017, Human Rights Watch described the legal age for marriage of girls as being 16, or 15 with the consent of the father or a judge.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] The most preferred marriage in Afghan society is to one's parallel cousin, and the groom is often expected to pay a bride price.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] In the villages, families typically occupy mudbrick houses, or compounds with mudbrick or stone walled houses.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Villages typically have a headman (*malik*), a master for water distribution (*mirab*) and a religious teacher (*mullah*).
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Men would typically work on the fields, joined by women during harvest.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] About 15% of the population are nomadic, locally called *kochis*.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] When nomads pass villages they often buy supplies such as tea, wheat and kerosene from the villagers; villagers buy wool and milk from the nomads.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Afghan clothing for both men and women typically consists of various forms of shalwar kameez, especially *perahan tunban* and *khet partug*.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Women would normally wear a *chador* for head covering; some women, typically from highly conservative communities, wear the *burqa*, a full body covering.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] These were worn by some women of the Pashtun community well before Islam came to the region, but the Taliban enforced this dress on women when they were in power.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Another popular dress is the *chapan* which acts as a coat.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] The *karakul* is a hat made from the fur of a specific regional breed of sheep.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] It was favored by former kings of Afghanistan and became known to much of the world in the 21st century when it was constantly worn by President Hamid Karzai.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] The *pakol* is another traditional hat originating from the far east of the country; it was popularly worn by the guerrilla leader Ahmad Shah Massoud.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] The *Mazari hat* originates from northern Afghanistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] The nation has a complex history that has survived either in its current cultures or in the form of various languages and monuments.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Afghanistan contains many remnants from all ages, including Greek and Buddhist stupas, monasteries, monuments, temples, and Islamic minarets.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Among the most well known are the Great Mosque of Herat, the Blue Mosque, the Minaret of Jam, the Chil Zena, the Qala-i Bost in Lashkargah, the ancient Greek city of Ai-Khanoum.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] However, many of its historic monuments have been damaged in modern times due to the civil wars.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] The two famous Buddhas of Bamiyan were destroyed by the Taliban, who regarded them as idolatrous.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] As there was no colonialism in the modern era in Afghanistan, European-style architecture is rare but does exist: the Victory Arch at Paghman and the Darul Aman Palace in Kabul were built in this style in the 1920s.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Afghan architecture also ranges deep into India such as the city of Agra, and the tomb of Sher Shah Suri, an Afghan Emperor of India.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Carpet weaving is an ancient practice in Afghanistan, and many of these are still handmade by tribal and nomadic people today.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Carpets have been produced in the region for thousands of years and traditionally done by women.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Some crafters express their feelings through the designs of rugs; for example after the outbreak of the Soviet–Afghan War, "war rugs", a variant of Afghan rugs, were created with designs representing pain and misery caused by the conflict.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Every province has its own specific characteristics in making rugs.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] In some of the Turkic-populated areas in the north-west, bride and wedding ceremony prices are driven by the bride's weaving skills.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Pottery has been crafted in Afghanistan for millennia.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] The village of Istalif, north of Kabul, is in particular a major center, known for its unique turquoise and green pottery, and their methods of crafting have remained the same for centuries.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Much of *lapis lazuli* stones were earthed in modern-day Afghanistan which were used in Chinese porcelain as cobalt blue, later used in ancient Mesopotamia and Turkey.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] The lands of Afghanistan have a long history of art, with the world's earliest known usage of oil painting found in cave murals in the country.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] A notable art style that developed in Afghanistan and eastern Pakistan is Gandhara Art, produced by a fusion of Greco-Roman art and Buddhist art between the 1st and 7th centuries CE.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Later eras saw increased use of the Persian miniature style, with Kamaleddin Behzad of Herat being one of the most notable miniature artists of the Timurid and early Safavid periods.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Since the 1900s, the nation began to use Western techniques in art.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Abdul Ghafoor Breshna was a prominent Afghan painter and sketch artist from Kabul during the 20th century.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Classic Persian and Pashto poetry are a cherished part of Afghan culture.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Poetry has always been one of the major educational pillars in the region, to the level that it has integrated itself into culture.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] One of the poetic styles is called landay.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] A popular theme in Afghan folklore and mythology are Divs, monstrous creatures.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Thursdays are traditionally "poetry night" in the city of Herat when men, women and children gather and recite both ancient and modern poems.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] The Afghan Pashto literature, although quantitatively remarkable and in great growth in the last century, has always had an essentially local meaning and importance, feeling the influence of both Persian literature and the contiguous literatures of India.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Both main literatures, from the second half of the nineteenth century, have shown themselves to be sensitive to genres, movements and stylistic features imported from Europe.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Khushal Khan Khattak of the 17th century is considered the national poet.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Other notable poets include Rabi'a Balkhi, Jami, Rahman Baba, Khalilullah Khalili, and Parween Pazhwak.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Afghan classical music has close historical links with Indian classical music and use the same Hindustani terminology and theories like raga.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Genres of this style of music include ghazal (poetic music) and instruments such as the Indian tabla, sitar and harmonium, and local instruments like zerbaghali, as well as dayereh and tanbur which are also known in Central Asia, the Caucasus and the Middle East.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] The rubab is the country's national instrument and precurses the Indian sarod instrument.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Some of the famous artists of classical music include Ustad Sarahang and Sarban.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Pop music developed in the 1950s through Radio Kabul and was influential in social change.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] During this time female artists also started appearing, at first Mermon Parwin.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Perhaps the most famous artist of this genre was Ahmad Zahir, who synthesized many genres and continues to be renowned for his voice and rich lyrics long after his death in 1979.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Other notable masters of traditional or popular Afghan music include Nashenas, Ubaidullah Jan, Mahwash, Ahmad Wali, Farhad Darya, and Naghma.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Attan is the national dance of Afghanistan, a group dance popularly performed by Afghans of all backgrounds.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] The dance is considered part of Afghan identity.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Afghanistan has around 350 radio stations and over 200 television stations.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Radio Television Afghanistan, originating from 1925, is the state public broadcaster.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Television programs began airing in the 1970s and today there are many private television channels such as TOLO and Shamshad TV.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] The first Afghan newspaper was published in 1873, and there are hundreds of print outlets today.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] By the 1920s, Radio Kabul was broadcasting local radio services.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Voice of America, BBC, and Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty (RFE/RL) broadcast in both of Afghanistan's official languages on radio.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Press restrictions have been gradually relaxed and private media diversified since 2002, after more than two decades of tight controls.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Afghans have long been accustomed to watching Indian Bollywood films and listening to its filmi songs.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] It has been claimed that Afghanistan is among the biggest markets for the Hindi film industry.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] The stereotypes of Afghans in India (*Kabuliwala* or *Pathani*) have also been represented in some Bollywood films by actors.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Many Bollywood film stars have roots in Afghanistan, including Salman Khan, Saif Ali Khan, Aamir Khan, Feroz Khan, Kader Khan, Naseeruddin Shah, Zarine Khan, Celina Jaitly, and a number of others.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Several Bollywood films have been shot inside Afghanistan, including *Dharmatma*, *Khuda Gawah*, *Escape from Taliban*, and *Kabul Express*.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Afghan cuisine is largely based upon the nation's chief crops, such as wheat, maize, barley and rice.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Accompanying these staples are native fruits and vegetables as well as dairy products such as milk, yogurt, and whey.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Kabuli palaw is the national dish of Afghanistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] The nation's culinary specialties reflect its ethnic and geographic diversity.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Afghanistan is known for its high-quality pomegranates, grapes, and sweet melons.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] A typical Afghan diet consists of naan, yogurt, rice, and meat.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Afghanistan's official New Year starts with Nowruz (natively known as "*Nawroz*"), an ancient tradition that started as a Zoroastrian celebration in present-day Iran, and with which it shares the annual celebration along with several other countries.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] It occurs every year at the vernal equinox.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] In Afghanistan, Nowruz is typically celebrated with music and dance, as well as holding buzkashi tournaments.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Yaldā, another nationally celebrated ancient tradition, commemorates the ancient goddess Mithra and marks the longest night of the year on the eve of the winter solstice (*Čilli-yi Zimistān*; usually falling on 20 or 21 December), during which families gather together to recite poetry and eat fruit.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] As a predominantly Muslim country, Islamic events and festivals such as Ramadan, Eid al-Fitr and Ashura are widely celebrated annually in Afghanistan.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] The Sikh festival of Vaisakhi is celebrated by the Sikh community and the Hindu festival Diwali by the Hindu community.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] National Independence Day is celebrated on 19 August to mark the Anglo-Afghan Treaty of 1919 and the country's full independence.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Several international celebrations are also officially held in Afghanistan, such as International Workers' Day, and International Women's Day.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Some regional festivals include the Red Flower Festival (during Nowruz) in Mazar-i-Sharif, and the Damboora Festival in Bamyan Province.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Sport in Afghanistan is managed by the Afghan Sports Federation.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Cricket and association football are the two most popular sports in the country.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] The Afghan Sports Federation promotes cricket, association football, basketball, volleyball, golf, handball, boxing, taekwondo, weightlifting, bodybuilding, track and field, skating, bowling, snooker, chess, and other sports.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] The Afghanistan national basketball team won the first team sports title at the 2010 South Asian Games.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] In 2012, the country's 3x3 basketball team won the gold medal at the 2012 Asian Beach Games.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] In 2013, Afghanistan's football team followed as it won the SAFF Championship.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] The Afghan national cricket team, which was formed in 2001, won the 2009–10 ICC Intercontinental Cup.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] The team played in the 2015, 2019, and 2023 Cricket World Cups.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] The Afghanistan Cricket Board (ACB) is the official governing body of the sport and is based in Kabul.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] The Alokozay Kabul International Cricket Ground serves as the nation's main cricket stadium.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] There are several other stadiums throughout the country, including the Ghazi Amanullah Khan International Cricket Stadium near Jalalabad.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] Domestically, cricket is played between teams from different provinces.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] The Afghanistan national football team has been competing in international football since 1941.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] The national team plays its home games at the Ghazi Stadium in Kabul, while football in Afghanistan is governed by the Afghanistan Football Federation.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] The national team has never competed or qualified for the FIFA World Cup but won an international football trophy in 2013.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] The country also has a national team in the sport of futsal, a 5-a-side variation of football.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] The traditional and the national sport of Afghanistan is buzkashi, particularly popular in the north.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] It is similar to polo, played by horsemen in two teams, each trying to grab and hold a goat carcass.
[src:almond/afghanistan-p03] The Afghan Hound (a type of running dog) originated in Afghanistan and was used in wolf hunting.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Children are particularly vulnerable to aflatoxin exposure, which is linked to immune suppression, stunted growth, delayed development, aflatoxicosis, and liver cancer.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Some studies have reported an association between childhood stunting and aflatoxin exposure, although this link has not been consistently detected in all studies.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Furthermore, a causal relationship between childhood stunting and aflatoxin exposure has yet to be conclusively shown by epidemiological studies, though such investigations are underway.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Adults have a higher tolerance to exposure, but are also at risk.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] No animal species is known to be immune.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Aflatoxins are among the most carcinogenic substances known.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] After entering the body, aflatoxins may be metabolized by the liver to a reactive epoxide intermediate or hydroxylated to become the less harmful aflatoxin M1.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Aflatoxin poisoning most commonly results from ingestion, but the most toxic aflatoxin compound, B1, can permeate through the skin.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] The United States Food and Drug Administration (FDA) action levels for aflatoxin present in food or feed is 20 to 300 ppb.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] The FDA has had occasion to declare both human and pet food recalls as a precautionary measure to prevent exposure.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] The term "aflatoxin" is derived from the name of the species *Aspergillus flavus*, in which some of the compounds were first discovered.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] A new disease was identified with unknown characteristics in England during the 1950s and 1960s, which increased turkey mortality.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Later, aflatoxin was recognized in 1960 in England as a causative agent of the mysterious Turkey X disease that causes excessive mortality in turkey poults.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Aflatoxins form one of the major groupings of mycotoxins.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Aflatoxin B1 is considered the most toxic and is produced by both *Aspergillus flavus* and *Aspergillus parasiticus*.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Aflatoxin M1 is present in the fermentation broth of *Aspergillus parasiticus*, but it and aflatoxin M2 are also produced when an infected liver metabolizes aflatoxin B1 and B2.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] AFM, AFQ, and AFL retain the possibility of becoming an epoxide.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Nevertheless, they appear much less capable of causing mutagenesis than the unmetabolized ABM.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] The staple commodities regularly contaminated with aflatoxins include cassava, chilies, corn, cottonseed, millet, peanuts, rice, sorghum, sunflower seeds, tree nuts, wheat, and a variety of spices intended for human or animal consumption.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Aflatoxins have been isolated from all major cereal crops, and sources as diverse as peanut butter and cannabis.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Aflatoxin transformation products are sometimes found in eggs, milk products, and meat when animals are fed contaminated grains.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Aflatoxins are produced by both *Aspergillus flavus* and *Aspergillus parasiticus*, which are common forms of "weedy" molds widespread in nature.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Aflatoxins occur also in *Aspergillus pseudocaelatus*, *Aspergillus nomius* and *Aspergillus pseudonomius*.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] The presence of these molds does not always indicate that harmful levels of aflatoxin are present, but it does indicate a significant risk.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] The molds can colonize and contaminate food before harvest or during storage, especially following prolonged exposure to a high-humidity environment or to stressful conditions such as drought.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Aflatoxin contamination is increasing in crops such as maize as a result of climate change.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] The native habitat of *Aspergillus* is in soil, decaying vegetation, hay, and grains undergoing microbiological deterioration, but it invades all types of organic substrates whenever conditions are favorable for its growth.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Favorable conditions for production of aflatoxins include high moisture content (at least 7%) and temperatures from 55 to 104 °F (13 to 40 °C), where the optimum is 27 to 30 °C (81 to 86 °F).
[src:almond/aflatoxin] A study conducted in Kenya and Mali found that the predominant practices for drying and storage of maize were inadequate in minimizing exposure to aflatoxins.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] A primary means of limiting risk from aflatoxins in the food supply is food hygiene in the commercial commodity supply chain, such as rejecting moldy grain for use in food processing plants and testing of batches of ingredients for aflatoxin levels before adding them to the mix.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Regulatory agencies such as the FDA set limits on acceptable levels.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Grain drying itself, which is necessary for viable combine harvesting in many regions, assists in this effort by preventing stored grain from being too damp in the first place.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] The use of nixtamalization, the processing of maize or other grains by soaking and cooking in alkali solution, greatly reduces aflatoxin concentrations.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] There is very limited evidence to show that agricultural and nutritional education can reduce exposure to aflatoxin in low to middle-income countries.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] No animal species is known to be immune to the acute toxic effects of aflatoxins.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Adult humans have a high tolerance for aflatoxin exposure and rarely succumb to acute aflatoxicosis, but children are particularly affected, and their exposure can lead to stunted growth and delayed development, in addition to all the symptoms mentioned below.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] High-level aflatoxin exposure produces an acute hepatic necrosis (acute aflatoxicosis), resulting later in cirrhosis or carcinoma of the liver.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Acute liver failure is made manifest by bleeding, edema, alteration in digestion, changes to the absorption and/or metabolism of nutrients, and mental changes and/or coma.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Chronic, subclinical exposure does not lead to symptoms as dramatic as acute aflatoxicosis.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Chronic exposure increases the risk of developing liver and gallbladder cancer, as aflatoxin metabolites may intercalate into DNA and alkylate the bases through its epoxide moiety.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] This is thought to cause mutations in the *p53* gene, an important gene in preventing cell cycle progression when there are DNA mutations, or signaling apoptosis (programmed cell death).
[src:almond/aflatoxin] These mutations seem to affect some base pair locations more than others; for example, the third base of codon 249 of the p53 gene appears to be more susceptible to aflatoxin-mediated mutations than nearby bases.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] As with other DNA-alkylating agents, Aflatoxin B1 can cause immune suppression, and exposure to it is associated with an increased viral load in HIV positive individuals.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] The expression of aflatoxin-related diseases is influenced by factors such as species, age, nutrition, sex, and the possibility of concurrent exposure to other toxins.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] The main target organ in mammals is the liver, so aflatoxicosis is primarily a hepatic disease.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Conditions increasing the likelihood of aflatoxicosis in humans include limited availability of food, environmental conditions that favor mold growth on foodstuffs, and lack of regulatory systems for aflatoxin monitoring and control.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] A regular diet including apiaceous vegetables, such as carrots, parsnips, celery, and parsley may reduce the carcinogenic effects of aflatoxin.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] There is no specific antidote for aflatoxicosis.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Symptomatic and supportive care tailored to the severity of the liver disease may include intravenous fluids with dextrose, active vitamin K, B vitamins, and a restricted, but high-quality protein diet with adequate carbohydrate content.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] In dogs, aflatoxin has the potential to lead to liver disease.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Low levels of aflatoxin exposure require continuous consumption for several weeks to months for signs of liver dysfunction to appear.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Some articles have suggested the toxic level in dog food is 100–300 ppb and requires continuous exposure or consumption for a few weeks to months to develop aflatoxicosis.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] No information is available to suggest that recovered dogs will later succumb to an aflatoxin-induced disease.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Turkeys are extremely susceptible to aflatoxicosis.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Recent studies have revealed that this is due to the efficient cytochrome P450 mediated metabolism of aflatoxin B1 in the liver of turkeys and deficient glutathione-S-transferase mediated detoxification.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Some studies on pregnant hamsters showed a significant relationship between exposure to aflatoxin B1 (4 mg/kg, single dose) and the appearance of developmental anomalies in their offspring.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Two principal techniques have been used most often to detect levels of aflatoxin in humans, though they are not commercially available.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] The first method is measuring the AFB1-guanine adduct in the urine of subjects.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] The presence of this breakdown product indicates exposure to aflatoxin B1 during the past 24 hours.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] This technique measures only recent exposure, however.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Due to the half-life of this metabolite, the level of AFB1-guanine measured may vary from day to day, based on diet, and it is not ideal for assessing long-term exposure.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] Another technique that has been used is a measurement of the AFB1-albumin adduct level in the blood serum.
[src:almond/aflatoxin] This approach provides a more integrated measure of exposure over several weeks or months.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] The **Agricultural Marketing Service** (**AMS**) is an agency of the United States Department of Agriculture; it maintains programs in five commodity areas: cotton and tobacco; dairy; fruit and vegetable; livestock and seed; and poultry.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] These programs provide testing, standardization, grading and market news services for those commodities, and oversee marketing agreements and orders, administer research and promotion programs, and purchase commodities for federal food programs.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] The AMS enforces certain federal laws such as the Perishable Agricultural Commodities Act and the Federal Seed Act.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] As of July 2021, AMS is led by Administrator Erin Morris.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] Established in 1939 by Agriculture Secretary Henry A.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] Most functions of the new Service were later consolidated into the Agricultural Marketing Administration in 1942 before being shifted again several times in the 1940s and 1950s.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] The agency was once renamed back into the AMS from 1953 to 1965 before becoming the Consumer and Marketing Service.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] In April 1972, the current structure of the AMS was officially established under the Department of Agriculture.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] AMS also began enforcing parts of the 1990 Organic Foods Production Act.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] Over the decades, AMS grew to also support ranchers, importers, exporters, and other agriculture industry groups.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] AMS' primary function is to market American agricultural products inside and outside the United States.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] In addition to this, AMS also funds, administers, and supports agricultural research; grades and certifies the safety of agricultural products; and disseminates information and expertise in the agriculture and agriculture marking industries.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] The Livestock and Poultry Program (L&P) supports federal food and nutrition programs like the National School Lunch Program (NSLP).
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] AMS also enforces the Perishable Agricultural Commodities Act (PACA), Federal Seed Act, Organic Foods Production Act, and Packers and Stockyards Act.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] The Warehouse and Commodity Management Division of the Fair Trade Practices Program administers United States Warehouse Act and Commodity Credit Corporation storage agreements.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] AMS is headed by the Office of the Administrator, Legislative and Regulatory Review Staff, Public Affairs Staff, and Administrative Management Staff.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] AMS is divided into nine programs and one service which are further subdivided into divisions and staffs.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] Additionally, AMS receives input and counsel from the Advisory Committee on Universal Cotton Standards, Fruit & Vegetable Industry Advisory Committee (FVIAC), Grain Inspection Advisory Committee, National Organic Standards Board (NOSB), and Plant Variety Protection Board.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] The AMS National Organic Program (NOP) develops, implements, and administers national production, handling, and labeling standards for organic agricultural products.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] The NOP also accredits the certifying agents (foreign and domestic) who inspect organic production and handling operations to certify that they meet USDA standards.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] The AMS Science and Technology Program provides scientific support services to the agricultural community and AMS programs, including laboratory analyses, laboratory quality assurance, and coordination of scientific research conducted by other agencies for AMS.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] In addition, the program's Plant Variety Protection Office administers the Plant Variety Protection Act, by issuing Certificates of Protection for new varieties of plants which are sexually reproduced (by seed) or tuber-propagated.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] The program also conducts a program to collect and analyze data about pesticide residue levels in agricultural commodities.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] It also administers the Pesticide Recordkeeping program, which requires all certified private applicators of federally restricted-use pesticide to maintain records of all applications.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] The records will be put into a data base to help analyze agricultural pesticide use.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] The AMS Transportation and Marketing Program supplies research and technical information regarding the nation's food transportation system to producers, producer groups, shippers, exporters, rural communities, carriers, government agencies and universities.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] The program also administers a program involving financial grants to States for marketing improvements.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] In addition, the division assists in the planning and design of marketing facilities, processes, and methods in cooperation with state and local governments, universities, farmer groups, and other segments of the U.S. food industry.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] This program is intended to enhance the overall effectiveness of the food marketing system, provide better quality products to the consumer at reasonable cost, improve market access for growers with farms of small to medium size, and promote regional economic development.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] The Commodity Procurement Program purchases a variety of domestically produced and processed commodity food products to support American agriculture by encouraging the consumption of domestic foods.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] The program also manages the Web-Based Supply Chain Management (WBSCM), a fully integrated, web-based ordering and procurement system used for the purchase of USDA Foods.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] Foods purchased by the program are delivered to schools, food banks, and households in communities across the country as a component of our nation’s food safety net.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] The program's International Commodity Procurement Division, purchases and delivers US-produced food aid commodities to vulnerable populations in foreign countries.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] The Dairy Program facilitates the efficient marketing of milk and dairy products.
[src:almond/agricultural-marketing-service] The AMS administers the commodity checkoff programs.
[src:almond/almond] ***Prunus dulcis*** (Mill.) D.A.Webb, nom. illeg. non *Prunus dulcis* Rouchy) is a species of tree from the genus *Prunus*.
[src:almond/almond] Along with the peach, it is classified in the subgenus *Amygdalus*, distinguished from the other subgenera by corrugations on the woody shell (endocarp) surrounding the seed.
[src:almond/almond] The fruit of the almond is a drupe, consisting of an outer hull and a hard shell with the seed, which is not a true nut.
[src:almond/almond] *Shelling* almonds refers to removing the shell to reveal the seed.
[src:almond/almond] Blanched almonds are unshelled almonds that have been treated with hot water to soften the outer skin, which is then removed to reveal the white embryo.
[src:almond/almond] Once almonds are cleaned and processed, they can be stored for around a year if kept refrigerated; at higher temperatures they will become rancid more quickly.
[src:almond/almond] Almonds are used in many cuisines, often featuring prominently in desserts, such as marzipan.
[src:almond/almond] The almond tree prospers in a moderate Mediterranean climate with cool winter weather.
[src:almond/almond] It is rarely found wild in its original setting.
[src:almond/almond] Almonds were one of the earliest domesticated fruit trees, due to the ability to produce quality offspring entirely from seed, without using suckers and cuttings.
[src:almond/almond] Evidence of domesticated almonds in the Early Bronze Age has been found in the archeological sites of the Middle East, and subsequently across the Mediterranean region and similar arid climates with cool winters.
[src:almond/almond] California produces about 80% of the world's almond supply.
[src:almond/almond] Due to high acreage and water demand for almond cultivation, and need for pesticides, California almond production may be unsustainable, especially during the persistent drought and heat from climate change in the 21st century.
[src:almond/almond] Droughts in California have caused some producers to leave the industry, leading to lower supply and increased prices.
[src:almond/almond] The almond is a deciduous tree growing to 3–4.5 metres (10–15 feet) in height, with a trunk of up to 30 centimetres (12 inches) in diameter.
[src:almond/almond] The young twigs are green at first, becoming purplish where exposed to sunlight, then grey in their second year.
[src:almond/almond] The leaves are 8–13 cm (3–5 in) long, with a serrated margin and a 2.5 cm (1 in) petiole.
[src:almond/almond] The fragrant flowers are white to pale pink, 3–5 cm (1–2 in) diameter with five petals, produced singly or in pairs and appearing before the leaves in early spring.
[src:almond/almond] Almond trees thrive in Mediterranean climates with warm, dry summers and mild, wet winters.
[src:almond/almond] The optimal temperature for their growth is between 15 and 30 °C (59 and 86 °F) and the tree buds have a chilling requirement of 200 to 700 hours below 7.2 °C (45.0 °F) to break dormancy.
[src:almond/almond] Almonds begin bearing an economic crop in the third year after planting.
[src:almond/almond] Trees reach full bearing five to six years after planting.
[src:almond/almond] The fruit matures in the autumn, 7–8 months after flowering.
[src:almond/almond] The outer covering, consisting of an outer exocarp, or skin, and mesocarp, or flesh, fleshy in other members of *Prunus* such as the plum and cherry, is instead a thick, leathery, grey-green coat (with a downy exterior), called the hull.
[src:almond/almond] Inside the hull is a woody endocarp which forms a reticulated, hard shell (like the outside of a peach pit) called the pyrena.
[src:almond/almond] Inside the shell is the edible seed, commonly called a nut.
[src:almond/almond] Generally, one seed is present, but occasionally two occur.
[src:almond/almond] After the fruit matures, the hull splits and separates from the shell, and an abscission layer forms between the stem and the fruit so that the fruit can fall from the tree.
[src:almond/almond] During harvest, mechanised tree shakers are used to expedite fruits falling to the ground for collection.
[src:almond/almond] The almond was named *Amygdalus communis* by Carl Linnaeus in his Species plantarum in 1753.
[src:almond/almond] For the name 'Amygdalus' he referred to Gaspard Bauhin's *Pinax* (1623).
[src:almond/almond] In 1801 the species was for the first time placed in the genus *Prunus* by August Batsch.
[src:almond/almond] In that genus, the name *Prunus communis* was no longer available because in 1778 William Hudson had already assigned it to a taxon in which he included the plum (*Prunus domestica*).
[src:almond/almond] Batsch thereupon named the species *Prunus amygdalus*, where 'amygdalus' is the old generic name and should therefore be treated as a noun in apposition.
[src:almond/almond] Meanwhile, in 1768, Philip Miller had published the name of what he believed to be a second species of almond: *Amygdalus dulcis*.
[src:almond/almond] He mentioned Linnaeus' *Amygdalus communis* as the first species.
[src:almond/almond] It was not until 1967 that the combination *Prunus dulcis* was published for the almond by David Allardice Webb, on the assumption that *Amygdalus dulcis* was nothing more than a synonym of *Amygdalus communis*, and thus an available name for that species.
[src:almond/almond] The epithet *dulcis* (1768) is older than *amygdalus* (1801) and would therefore have priority.
[src:almond/almond] Webb noted that it was unfortunate that a species known for 165 years as *Prunus amygdalus* now had to be renamed under the rules of nomenclature.
[src:almond/almond] However, it later turned out that in 1967 the name *Prunus dulcis* was no longer available for the almond because it had already been used for a cherry in an 1878 publication by L'Abbé Rouchy.
[src:almond/almond] The oldest valid combination in *Prunus* is therefore *Prunus amygdalus*.
[src:almond/almond] *dulcis* are predominantly sweet but some individual trees produce seeds that are somewhat more bitter.
[src:almond/almond] The genetic basis for bitterness involves a single gene, the bitter flavour furthermore being recessive, both aspects making this trait easier to domesticate.
[src:almond/almond] *amara* are always bitter, as are the kernels from other species of genus *Prunus*, such as apricot, peach and cherry (although to a lesser extent).
[src:almond/almond] The bitter almond is slightly broader and shorter than the sweet almond and contains about 50% of the fixed oil that occurs in sweet almonds.
[src:almond/almond] It contains the enzyme emulsin which, in the presence of water, acts on the two soluble glucosides amygdalin and prunasin yielding glucose, cyanide and the essential oil of bitter almonds, which is nearly pure benzaldehyde, the chemical causing the bitter flavour.
[src:almond/almond] Bitter almonds may yield 4–9 milligrams of hydrogen cyanide per almond and contain 42 times higher amounts of cyanide than the trace levels found in sweet almonds.
[src:almond/almond] The origin of cyanide content in bitter almonds is via the enzymatic hydrolysis of amygdalin.
[src:almond/almond] P450 monooxygenases are involved in the amygdalin biosynthetic pathway.
[src:almond/almond] A point mutation in a bHLH transcription factor prevents transcription of the two cytochrome P450 genes, resulting in the sweet kernel trait.
[src:almond/almond] The word *almond* is a loanword from Old French *almande* or *alemande*, descended from Late Latin *amandula*, *amindula*, modified from Classical Latin *amygdala*, which is in turn borrowed from Ancient Greek *amygdálē* (ἀμυγδάλη) (cf. amygdala, an almond-shaped portion of the brain).
[src:almond/almond] Late Old English had *amygdales* 'almonds'.
[src:almond/almond] The adjective *amygdaloid* (literally 'like an almond, almond-like') is used to describe objects which are roughly almond-shaped, particularly a shape which is part way between a triangle and an ellipse.
[src:almond/almond] For example, the amygdala of the brain uses a direct borrowing of the Greek term *amygdalē*.
[src:almond/almond] The precise origin of the almond is controversial due to estimates for its emergence across wide geographic regions.
[src:almond/almond] Sources indicate that its origins were in an area stretching across Central Asia, Iran, Turkmenistan, Tajikistan, Kurdistan, Afghanistan, and Iraq, or in an eastern Asian subregion between Mongolia and Uzbekistan.
[src:almond/almond] In other assessments, both botanical and archaeological evidence indicates that almonds originated and were first cultivated in West Asia, particularly in countries of the Levant.
[src:almond/almond] Most recent sources specified Iran and Anatolia (present day Turkey) as origin locations of the almond, with Iran as the main origin centre.
[src:almond/almond] The wild form of domesticated almond grew in parts of the Levant.
[src:almond/almond] Almond cultivation was spread by humans centuries ago along the shores of the Mediterranean Sea into northern Africa and southern Europe, and more recently to other world regions, notably California.
[src:almond/almond] Selection of the sweet type from the many bitter types in the wild marked the beginning of almond domestication.
[src:almond/almond] The wild ancestor of the almond used to breed the domesticated species is unknown.
[src:almond/almond] The species *Prunus fenzliana* may be the most likely wild ancestor of the almond, in part because it is native to Armenia and western Azerbaijan, where it was apparently domesticated.
[src:almond/almond] Wild almond species were grown by early farmers, "at first unintentionally in the garbage heaps, and later intentionally in their orchards".
[src:almond/almond] Almonds were one of the earliest domesticated fruit trees owing to their ability to be grown from seed, allowing their cultivation to have perhaps predated the advent of grafting.
[src:almond/almond] Domesticated almonds appear in the Early Bronze Age (3000–2000 BCE), such as the archaeological sites of Numeira (Jordan), or possibly earlier.
[src:almond/almond] They were found in Tutankhamun's tomb in Egypt (c.
[src:almond/almond] 1325 BCE), probably imported from the Levant.
[src:almond/almond] Ibn al-'Awwam's 12th-century *Book on Agriculture* includes an article on almond tree cultivation in Spain.
[src:almond/almond] Of the European countries that the Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh reported as cultivating almonds, Germany is the northernmost, though the domesticated form can be found as far north as Iceland.
[src:almond/almond] Almond trees are small to medium-sized but commercial cultivars can be grafted onto a different root-stock to produce smaller trees.
[src:almond/almond] Breeding programs have found a high shell-seal trait, which reduces insect damage and mold contamination.
[src:almond/almond] The most widely planted varieties of almond are self-incompatible; hence these trees require pollen from a tree with different genetic characters to produce seeds.
[src:almond/almond] Almond orchards therefore must grow mixtures of almond varieties.
[src:almond/almond] In addition, the pollen is transferred from flower to flower by insects; therefore commercial growers must ensure there are enough insects to perform this task.
[src:almond/almond] The large scale of almond production in the U.S. creates a significant problem of providing enough pollinating insects.
[src:almond/almond] Additional pollinating insects are therefore brought to the trees.
[src:almond/almond] The pollination of California's almonds is the largest annual managed pollination event in the world, with over 1 million hives (nearly half of all beehives in the U.S.) being brought to the almond orchards each February.
[src:almond/almond] Much of the supply of bees is managed by pollination brokers, who contract with migratory beekeepers from at least 49 states for the event.
[src:almond/almond] This business was heavily affected by colony collapse disorder at the turn of the 21st century, causing a nationwide shortage of honey bees and increasing the price of insect pollination.
[src:almond/almond] To partially protect almond growers from these costs, researchers at the Agricultural Research Service, part of the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA), developed self-pollinating almond trees that combine this character with quality characters such as a flavour and yield.
[src:almond/almond] Almond trees can be attacked by an array of damaging microbes, fungal pathogens, plant viruses, and bacteria.
[src:almond/almond] Pavement ants (*Tetramorium caespitum*), southern fire ants (*Solenopsis xyloni*), and thief ants (*Solenopsis molesta*) are seed predators.
[src:almond/almond] *Bryobia rubrioculus* mites are most known for their damage to this crop.
[src:almond/almond] Almond production in California is concentrated mainly in the Central Valley, where the mild climate, rich soil, abundant sunshine and water supply make for ideal growing conditions.
[src:almond/almond] Due to the persistent droughts in California in the early 21st century, it became more difficult to raise almonds in a sustainable manner.
[src:almond/almond] The issue is complex because of the high amount of water needed to produce almonds: a single almond requires roughly 1.1 US gallons (0.92 imperial gallons; 4.2 litres) of water to grow properly.
[src:almond/almond] Regulations related to water supplies are changing so some growers have destroyed their current almond orchards to replace with either younger trees or a different crop such as pistachio that needs less water.
[src:almond/almond] California almond farmers have promoted growing use of sustainable farming practices, including introduction of water-efficient irrigation technology, funding of honeybee health research, and productively using waste biomass (such as shells) in pursuit of a zero waste industry.
[src:almond/almond] In 2023, world production of almonds was 3.5 million tonnes, led by the United States with 51% of the total, followed by Spain and Australia as secondary producers (table).
[src:almond/almond] Australia is the largest almond production region in the Southern Hemisphere.
[src:almond/almond] Most of the country's almond orchards are located along the Murray River corridor in New South Wales, Victoria, or South Australia.
[src:almond/almond] In the Australian financial year 1 July 2024–30 June 2025, the national almond crop fell 5%, but increased in value by 20%, to a record A$1.3 billion.
[src:almond/almond] India was the second-largest export market, at 19,803 t (19,490 long tons; 21,829 short tons), a tonnage similar to that of the previous financial year.
[src:almond/almond] As of late February 2026, Australia was forecast to harvest a record almond crop of 167,000 t (164,000 long tons; 184,000 short tons) in the 2025–26 financial year.
[src:almond/almond] Spain has diverse commercial cultivars of almonds grown in Catalonia, Valencia, Murcia, Andalusia, and Aragón regions, and the Balearic Islands.
[src:almond/almond] The almond cultivar 'Marcona' is unique, having a kernel that is short, round, relatively sweet, and delicate in texture; it is marketed by name.
[src:almond/almond] Its origin is unknown, but has been grown in Spain over centuries.
[src:almond/almond] In the U.S., production is concentrated in California where 400,000 ha (1,000,000 acres) and six different almond varieties were under cultivation in 2017, with a yield of 2.25 billion pounds (1.02 billion kilograms) of shelled almonds.
[src:almond/almond] California production is marked by a period of intense pollination during late winter by rented commercial bees transported by truck across the U.S. to almond groves, requiring more than half of the total U.S. commercial honeybee population.
[src:almond/almond] The value of total U.S. exports of shelled almonds in 2016 was $3.2 billion.
[src:almond/almond] All commercially grown almonds sold as food in the U.S. are sweet cultivars.
[src:almond/almond] Food and Drug Administration reported in 2010 that some fractions of imported sweet almonds were contaminated with bitter almonds, which contain cyanide.
[src:almond/almond] Bitter almonds contain some 40 times the trace levels of cyanide found in sweet almonds.
[src:almond/almond] Extract of bitter almond was once used medicinally, but even in small doses, its effects are severe or lethal, especially in children; the cyanide must be removed before consumption.
[src:almond/almond] The acute oral lethal dose of cyanide for adult humans is reported to be 0.5–3.5 mg/kg (0.2–1.6 mg/lb) of body weight (approximately 50 bitter almonds for the average adult), so that for children consuming 5–10 bitter almonds may be fatal.
[src:almond/almond] Symptoms of eating such almonds include vertigo and other typical cyanide poisoning effects.
[src:almond/almond] Almonds may cause allergy or intolerance.
[src:almond/almond] Cross-reactivity is common with peach allergens (lipid transfer proteins) and tree nut allergens.
[src:almond/almond] Symptoms range from local signs and symptoms (e.g., oral allergy syndrome, contact urticaria) to systemic signs and symptoms including anaphylaxis (e.g., urticaria, angioedema, gastrointestinal and respiratory symptoms).
[src:almond/almond] Almonds are susceptible to aflatoxin-producing moulds.
[src:almond/almond] Aflatoxins are potent carcinogenic chemicals produced by moulds such as *Aspergillus flavus* and *Aspergillus parasiticus*.
[src:almond/almond] The mould contamination may occur from soil, previously infested almonds, and almond pests such as navel-orange worm.
[src:almond/almond] High levels of mould growth typically appear as grey to black filament-like growth.
[src:almond/almond] It is unsafe to eat mould-infected tree nuts.
[src:almond/almond] Some countries have strict limits on allowable levels of aflatoxin contamination of almonds and require adequate testing before the nuts can be marketed to their citizens.
[src:almond/almond] The European Union, for example, introduced a requirement since 2007 that all almond shipments to the EU be tested for aflatoxin.
[src:almond/almond] If aflatoxin does not meet the strict safety regulations, either the entire consignment must be reprocessed to eliminate the aflatoxin or it must be destroyed.
[src:almond/almond] After tracing cases of salmonellosis to almonds, the USDA approved a proposal by the Almond Board of California to pasteurize almonds sold to the public.
[src:almond/almond] After publishing the rule in March 2007, the almond pasteurization program became mandatory for California companies effective 1 September 2007.
[src:almond/almond] Raw, untreated California almonds have not been commercially available in the U.S. since then.
[src:almond/almond] California almonds labelled "raw" must be steam-pasteurized or chemically treated with propylene oxide (PPO).
[src:almond/almond] This does not apply to imported almonds or almonds sold from the grower directly to the consumer in small quantities.
[src:almond/almond] The Almond Board of California states: "PPO residue dissipates after treatment".
[src:almond/almond] Environmental Protection Agency has reported: "Propylene oxide has been detected in fumigated food products; consumption of contaminated food is another possible route of exposure".
[src:almond/almond] PPO is classified as Group 2B ("possibly carcinogenic to humans").
[src:almond/almond] The USDA-approved marketing order was challenged in court by organic farmers organized by the Cornucopia Institute, a Wisconsin-based farm policy research group which filed a lawsuit in September 2008.
[src:almond/almond] According to the institute, this almond marketing order has imposed significant financial burdens on small-scale and organic growers and damaged domestic almond markets.
[src:almond/almond] A federal judge dismissed the lawsuit in early 2009 on procedural grounds.
[src:almond/almond] In August 2010, a federal appeals court ruled that the farmers have a right to appeal the USDA regulation.
[src:almond/almond] In March 2013, the court vacated the suit on the basis that the objections should have been raised in 2007 when the regulation was first proposed.
[src:almond/almond] Almonds are 4% water, 22% carbohydrates, 21% protein, and 50% fat (table).
[src:almond/almond] Per 100 g, almonds contain dietary fiber (12 g), the monounsaturated fat, oleic acid (31 g), and the polyunsaturated fat, linoleic acid (12 g; table source).
[src:almond/almond] Typical of nuts and seeds, almonds are a source of phytosterols, such as beta-sitosterol.
[src:almond/almond] Almonds are included as a good source of protein among recommended healthy foods by the USDA.
[src:almond/almond] A 2016 review of clinical research indicated that regular consumption of almonds may reduce the risk of heart disease by lowering blood levels of LDL cholesterol.
[src:almond/almond] While the almond is often eaten on its own, raw or toasted, it is also a component of various dishes.
[src:almond/almond] Almonds are available in many forms, such as whole, slivered, and ground into flour.
[src:almond/almond] Almond pieces around 2–3 millimetres (1⁄16–1⁄8 in) in size, called "nibs", are used for special purposes such as decoration.
[src:almond/almond] A wide range of classic sweets feature almonds as a central ingredient.
[src:almond/almond] Marzipan was developed in the Middle Ages.
[src:almond/almond] Since the 19th century almonds have been used to make bread, almond butter, cakes and puddings, candied confections, almond cream-filled pastries, nougat, cookies (macaroons, biscotti and qurabiya), and cakes (financiers, Esterházy torte), and other sweets and desserts.
[src:almond/almond] In Saudi Arabia, almonds are a typical embellishment for the rice dish kabsa.
[src:almond/almond] Spanish cookery uses almonds in sweet dishes as well as in savory ones, ground up to thicken sauces and stews.
[src:almond/almond] Almonds can be processed into a milk substitute called almond milk; the nut's soft texture, mild flavour, and light colouring (when skinned) make for an efficient analog to dairy, and a soy-free choice for lactose intolerant people and vegans.
[src:almond/almond] Raw, blanched, and lightly toasted almonds work well for different production techniques, some of which are similar to that of soy milk and some of which use no heat, resulting in raw milk.
[src:almond/almond] Almond milk, along with almond butter and almond oil, are versatile products used in both sweet and savoury dishes.
[src:almond/almond] In Moroccan cuisine, sharbat billooz, a common beverage, is made by blending blanched almonds with milk, sugar and other flavourings.
[src:almond/almond] Almond flour or ground almond meal combined with sugar or honey as marzipan is often used as a gluten-free alternative to wheat flour in cooking and baking.
[src:almond/almond] Almonds contain polyphenols in their skins consisting of flavonols, flavan-3-ols, hydroxybenzoic acids and flavanones analogous to those of certain fruits and vegetables.
[src:almond/almond] These phenolic compounds and almond skin prebiotic dietary fibre have commercial interest as food additives or dietary supplements.
[src:almond/almond] Historically, almond syrup was an emulsion of sweet and bitter almonds, usually made with barley syrup (orgeat syrup) or in a syrup of orange flower water and sugar, often flavoured with a synthetic aroma of almonds.
[src:almond/almond] Orgeat syrup is an important ingredient in the Mai Tai and many other Tiki drinks.
[src:almond/almond] Due to the cyanide found in bitter almonds, modern syrups generally are produced only from sweet almonds.
[src:almond/almond] Such syrup products do not contain significant levels of hydrocyanic acid, so are generally considered safe for human consumption.
[src:almond/almond] Almonds are a rich source of oil, with 50% of kernel dry mass as fat (whole almond nutrition table).
[src:almond/almond] In relation to total dry mass of the kernel, almond oil contains 32% monounsaturated oleic acid (an omega-9 fatty acid), 13% linoleic acid (a polyunsaturated omega-6 essential fatty acid), and 10% saturated fatty acid (mainly as palmitic acid).
[src:almond/almond] Linolenic acid, a polyunsaturated omega-3 fat, is not present (table).
[src:almond/almond] When almond oil is analyzed separately and expressed per 100 grams as a reference mass, the oil provides 3,700 kJ (884 kcal) of food energy, 8 grams of saturated fat (81% of which is palmitic acid), 70 grams of oleic acid, and 17 grams of linoleic acid (oil table).
[src:almond/almond] The almond is highly revered in some cultures.
[src:almond/almond] In the Bible, the almond is mentioned ten times, beginning with Genesis 43:11, where it is described as "among the best of fruits".
[src:almond/almond] In Numbers 17, Levi is chosen from the other tribes of Israel by Aaron's rod, which brought forth almond flowers.
[src:almond/almond] In Jeremiah 1:11–12, the vision of an almond branch conveys a wordplay in Hebrew between *shaqed* (almond) and *shoqed* (watching), symbolizing God's vigilant commitment to fulfill His word.
[src:almond/almond] Many Sephardic Jews give five almonds to each guest before special occasions like weddings.
[src:almond/almond] Similarly, Christian symbolism often uses almond branches as a symbol of the virgin birth of Jesus; paintings and icons often include almond-shaped haloes encircling the Christ Child and as a symbol of Mary.
[src:almond/almond] The word "luz", which appears in Genesis 30:37, sometimes translated as "hazel", may actually be derived from the Aramaic name for almond (Luz), and is translated as such in the New International Version and other versions of the Bible.
[src:almond/almond] The Entrance of the flower (*La entrada de la flor*) is an event celebrated on 1 February in Torrent, Spain, in which the clavarios and members of the Confrerie of the Mother of God deliver a branch of the first-blooming almond-tree to the Virgin.
